# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ccpa-privacy
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ccpa-privacy/california-consumer-privacy-act] The **California Consumer Privacy Act** (**CCPA**) is a state statute intended to enhance privacy rights and consumer protection for residents of the state of California in the United States.
[src:ccpa-privacy/california-consumer-privacy-act] The bill was passed by the California State Legislature and signed into law by the Governor of California, Jerry Brown, on June 28, 2018, to amend Part 4 of Division 3 of the California Civil Code.
[src:ccpa-privacy/california-consumer-privacy-act] Officially called **AB-375**, the act was introduced by Ed Chau, member of the California State Assembly, and State Senator Robert Hertzberg.
[src:ccpa-privacy/california-consumer-privacy-act] Amendments to the CCPA, in the form of Senate Bill 1121, were passed on September 13, 2018.
[src:ccpa-privacy/california-consumer-privacy-act] Additional substantive amendments were signed into law on October 11, 2019.
[src:ccpa-privacy/california-consumer-privacy-act] The CCPA became effective on January 1, 2020.
[src:ccpa-privacy/california-consumer-privacy-act] In November 2020, California voters passed Proposition 24, also known as the California Privacy Rights Act, which amends and expands the CCPA.
[src:ccpa-privacy/california-consumer-privacy-act] Not be discriminated against for exercising their privacy rights.
[src:ccpa-privacy/california-consumer-privacy-act] Organizations are required to "implement and maintain reasonable security procedures and practices" in protecting consumer data.
[src:ccpa-privacy/california-consumer-privacy-act] The businesses that the CCPA refers to do not need to be physically present in California.
[src:ccpa-privacy/california-consumer-privacy-act] As long as the business is active in the state and meets the requirements, they are considered to be under the CCPA.
[src:ccpa-privacy/california-consumer-privacy-act] This includes transactions done on the Internet.
[src:ccpa-privacy/california-consumer-privacy-act] In comparison to other privacy laws like the GDPR, the CCPA lacks clarity about its geographic range.
[src:ccpa-privacy/california-consumer-privacy-act] The CCPA differs from the Virginia Consumer Data Protection Act in that the former provides a private right of action, whereas the latter is enforced by the Attorney General's office.
[src:ccpa-privacy/california-consumer-privacy-act] It does not consider *Publicly Available Information* as personal.
[src:ccpa-privacy/california-consumer-privacy-act] Key differences between CCPA and the European Union's General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR) include the scope and territorial reach of each, definitions related to protected information, levels of specificity, and an opt-out right for sales of personal information.
[src:ccpa-privacy/california-consumer-privacy-act] CCPA differs in definition of personal information from GDPR as in some cases the CCPA only considers data that was provided by a consumer.
[src:ccpa-privacy/california-consumer-privacy-act] The GDPR does not make that distinction and covers all personal data regardless of source.
[src:ccpa-privacy/california-consumer-privacy-act] In the event of sensitive personal information, this does not apply if the information was manifestly made public by the data subject themselves, following the exception under Art.9(2),e).
[src:ccpa-privacy/california-consumer-privacy-act] As such, the definition in GDPR is much broader than defined in the CCPA.
[src:ccpa-privacy/california-consumer-privacy-act] Personal data can also include online or social media profile information.
[src:ccpa-privacy/california-consumer-privacy-act] Personal data is not limited to a number or a physical document but can also be online identities, accounts, and other personal information.
[src:ccpa-privacy/california-consumer-privacy-act] The California Consumer Privacy Act of 2018 was originally proposed as a ballot proposition by a privacy group known as Californians for Consumer Privacy.
[src:ccpa-privacy/california-consumer-privacy-act] The California DOJ approved the initiative's official language on December 18, 2017, allowing the group to begin collecting signatures.
[src:ccpa-privacy/california-consumer-privacy-act] In June 2018, the proponents gathered enough signatures to qualify the CCPA initiative for the November 2018 election.
[src:ccpa-privacy/california-consumer-privacy-act] In California, the state legislature cannot repeal or amend a ballot proposition once it is passed by voters.
[src:ccpa-privacy/california-consumer-privacy-act] In response to the CCPA ballot proposition, state legislators negotiated with Californians for Consumer Privacy to pass a less restrictive version of the CCPA in exchange for the withdrawal of the ballot proposition.
[src:ccpa-privacy/california-consumer-privacy-act] The CCPA was passed by the state legislature and signed by Gov.
[src:ccpa-privacy/california-consumer-privacy-act] Brown on June 28, 2018; it became effective on January 1, 2020.
[src:ccpa-privacy/california-consumer-privacy-act] The act's effect was dependent upon the withdrawal of initiative 17–0039, the Consumer Right to Privacy Act.
[src:ccpa-privacy/california-consumer-privacy-act] Five amendments were enacted and signed by Gov.
[src:ccpa-privacy/california-consumer-privacy-act] Notice of DOJ's proposed regulations was also published October 11 in the Z Register; As of January 10, 2020 the OAL had not yet filed the final regulations with the Secretary of State, as required for the regulations to become effective.
[src:ccpa-privacy/california-consumer-privacy-act] The California Privacy Rights Act of 2020 proposed several changes to the CCPA.
[src:ccpa-privacy/california-consumer-privacy-act] The Act, also known as 2020 California Proposition 24, expands existing data privacy laws by allowing consumers greater control of their personal data and establishing the California Privacy Protection Agency.
[src:ccpa-privacy/california-consumer-privacy-act] It passed, with a majority of voters approving the measure.
[src:ccpa-privacy/california-consumer-privacy-act] A big area of the CCPA exemption is the personal health information (PHI) that is gathered.
[src:ccpa-privacy/california-consumer-privacy-act] Rather than the data being treated with the CCPA guidelines in mind, it is expected for PHI to adhere to the Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act, otherwise known as HIPAA.
[src:ccpa-privacy/california-consumer-privacy-act] If the business collecting the data is related to clinical trials, then it must adhere to the "Common Rule".
[src:ccpa-privacy/california-consumer-privacy-act] As for the information that is gathered by financial institutions, the institutions follow the California Financial Information Privacy act or the Gramm-Leach-Bliley Act depending on the situation.
[src:ccpa-privacy/consumer-privacy] A variety of social, legal and political issues arise from the interaction of the public's potential expectation of privacy and the collection and dissemination of data by businesses or merchants.
[src:ccpa-privacy/consumer-privacy] Consumer privacy concerns date back to the first commercial couriers and bankers who enforced strong measures to protect customer privacy.
[src:ccpa-privacy/consumer-privacy] In modern times, the ethical codes of various professions specify measures to protect customer privacy, including medical privacy and client confidentiality.
[src:ccpa-privacy/consumer-privacy] State interests include matters of national security.
[src:ccpa-privacy/consumer-privacy] Consumer concerned about the invasion of individual information, thus doubtful when thinking about using certain services.
[src:ccpa-privacy/consumer-privacy] Many organizations have a competitive incentive to collect, retain, and use customer data for various purposes, and many companies adopt security engineering measures to control this data and manage customer expectations and legal requirements for consumer privacy.
[src:ccpa-privacy/consumer-privacy] Businesses have consumer data and information obtained from consumer and client purchases, products, and services.
[src:ccpa-privacy/consumer-privacy] Thus, businesses have the responsibility to keep these data and information safe and confidential.
[src:ccpa-privacy/consumer-privacy] Consumers expect that businesses will take an active stance when protecting consumer privacy issues and supporting confidential agreements.
[src:ccpa-privacy/consumer-privacy] Whether a firm provides services or products to consumers, firms are expected to use methods such as obfuscation or encoding methods to cover up consumer data when analyzing data or trends for example.
[src:ccpa-privacy/consumer-privacy] Firms are also expected to protect consumer privacy both within the organizations themselves and from outside third entities including third party providers of services, suppliers who provide product components and supplies, and government institutions or community partnership organizations.
[src:ccpa-privacy/consumer-privacy] In addition, businesses are sometime required to provide an agreement/contract to service clients or product consumer that states customer or client information and data will be kept confidential and that it will not be used for advertising or promotional purposes for example.
[src:ccpa-privacy/consumer-privacy] The US government, including the FTC, have consumer protection laws like The Telephone Consumer Protection Act and Data Transparency and Privacy Act.
[src:ccpa-privacy/consumer-privacy] Individuals States have laws and regulation that protect consumers as well.
[src:ccpa-privacy/consumer-privacy] One example of this is The California Consumer Privacy Act.
[src:ccpa-privacy/consumer-privacy] Harsh punitive measures were passed as the result of failing to keep a customer's information private.
[src:ccpa-privacy/consumer-privacy] In modern times, the ethical codes of most professions specify privacy measures for the consumer of any service, including medical privacy, client confidentiality, and national security.
[src:ccpa-privacy/consumer-privacy] These codes are particularly important in a carceral state, where no privacy in any form nor limits on state oversight or data use exists.
[src:ccpa-privacy/consumer-privacy] *Corporate customer privacy practices* are approaches taken by commercial organizations to ensure that confidential customer data is not stolen or abused.
[src:ccpa-privacy/consumer-privacy] Since most organizations have strong competitive incentives to retain exclusive access to customer data, and since customer trust is usually a high priority, most companies take some security engineering measures to protect customer privacy.
[src:ccpa-privacy/consumer-privacy] There is also a concern that companies may sell consumer data if they have to declare bankruptcy, although it often violates their own privacy policies.
[src:ccpa-privacy/consumer-privacy] The California Consumer Privacy Act, for example, protects the use of consumer privacy data by firms and governments.
[src:ccpa-privacy/consumer-privacy] This act makes it harder for firms to extract personal information from consumers and use it for commercial purposes.
[src:ccpa-privacy/consumer-privacy] Some of the rights included in this act include: Penalties for non-compliance with CCPA can include fines ranging from $2,500 to $7,500 per violation, depending on the severity.
[src:ccpa-privacy/consumer-privacy] Since companies operate to generate a profit, commercial organizations also cannot spend unlimited funds on precautions while remaining competitive; a commercial context tends to limit privacy measures and to motivate organizations to share data when working in partnership.
[src:ccpa-privacy/consumer-privacy] The damage done by privacy loss is not measurable, nor can it be undone, and commercial organizations have little or no interest in taking unprofitable measures to drastically increase the privacy of customers.
[src:ccpa-privacy/consumer-privacy] Corporations may be inclined to share data for commercial advantage and fail to officially recognize it as sensitive to avoid legal liability in the chance that lapses of security may occur.
[src:ccpa-privacy/consumer-privacy] This has led to many moral hazards and customer privacy violation incidents.
[src:ccpa-privacy/consumer-privacy] Some services—notably telecommunications, including Internet—require collecting a vast array of information about users' activities in the course of business, and may also require consultation of these data to prepare bills.
[src:ccpa-privacy/consumer-privacy] In the US and Canada, telecom data must be kept for seven years to permit dispute and consultation about phone charges.
[src:ccpa-privacy/consumer-privacy] These sensitivities have led telecom regulation to be a leader in consumer privacy regulation, enforcing a high level of confidentiality on the sensitive customer communication records.
[src:ccpa-privacy/consumer-privacy] The focus of consumer rights activists on the telecoms industry has super-sided as other industries also gather sensitive consumer data.
[src:ccpa-privacy/consumer-privacy] Such common commercial measures as software-based customer relationship management, rewards programs, and target marketing tend to drastically increase the amount of information gathered (and sometimes shared).
[src:ccpa-privacy/consumer-privacy] These very drastically increase privacy risks and have accelerated the shift to regulation, rather than relying on the corporate desire to preserve goodwill.
[src:ccpa-privacy/consumer-privacy] Concerns have led to consumer privacy laws in most countries, especially in the European Union, Australia, New Zealand and Canada.
[src:ccpa-privacy/consumer-privacy] Notably, among developed countries, the United States has no such law and relies on corporate customer privacy disclosed in privacy policies to ensure consumer privacy in general.
[src:ccpa-privacy/consumer-privacy] Telephone operators could frequently hear conversations—inadvertently or deliberately—and their job required them to dial the exact numbers.
[src:ccpa-privacy/consumer-privacy] The data gathering required for the process of billing began to become a privacy risk as well.
[src:ccpa-privacy/consumer-privacy] Accordingly, strong rules on operator behaviour, customer confidentiality, records keeping and destruction were enforced on telephone companies in every country.
[src:ccpa-privacy/consumer-privacy] Typically only police and military authorities had legal powers to wiretap or see records.
[src:ccpa-privacy/consumer-privacy] Even stricter requirements emerged for various banks' electronic records.
[src:ccpa-privacy/consumer-privacy] In some countries, financial privacy is a major focus of the economy, with severe criminal penalties for violating it.
[src:ccpa-privacy/consumer-privacy] Through the 1970s, many other organizations in developed nations began to acquire sensitive data, but there were few or no regulations in place to prevent them from sharing or abusing the data.
[src:ccpa-privacy/consumer-privacy] Customer trust and goodwill were generally thought to be sufficient in first-world countries, notably the United States, to ensure the protection of truly sensitive data; *caveat emptor* was applied in these situations.
[src:ccpa-privacy/consumer-privacy] But in the 1980s, smaller organizations also began to get access to computer hardware and software, and these simply did not have the procedures or personnel or expertise, nor less the time, to take rigorous measures to protect their customers.
[src:ccpa-privacy/consumer-privacy] Meanwhile, via target marketing and rewards programs, companies were acquiring ever more data.
[src:ccpa-privacy/consumer-privacy] Gradually, customer privacy measures were seen as deficient to deal with the many hazards of corporate data sharing, corporate mergers, employee turnover, and theft of data storage devices (e.g. hard drives) that could store a large amount of data in a portable location.
[src:ccpa-privacy/consumer-privacy] In Austria around the 1990s, the mere mention of a client's name in a semi-public social setting was enough to earn a junior bank executive a stiff jail sentence.
[src:ccpa-privacy/consumer-privacy] After the terrorist attacks against the United States on September 11, 2001, privacy took a back-seat to national security in legislators' minds.
[src:ccpa-privacy/consumer-privacy] Accordingly, concerns of consumer privacy in the United States have tended to go unheard of as questions of citizen privacy versus the state, and the development of a police state or carceral state, have occupied advocates of strong privacy measures.
[src:ccpa-privacy/consumer-privacy] Whereas it may have appeared prior to 2002 that commercial organizations and the consumer data they gathered were of primary concern, it has appeared since then in most developed nations to be much less of a concern than political privacy and medical privacy (e.g., as violated by biometrics).
[src:ccpa-privacy/consumer-privacy] Indeed, people have recently been stopped at airports solely due to their political views, and there appears to be minimal public will to stop practices of this nature.
[src:ccpa-privacy/consumer-privacy] The need for stricter laws is more pronounced after the American web service provider, Yahoo admitted that sensitive information (including email addresses and passwords) of half a billion users was stolen by hackers in 2014.
[src:ccpa-privacy/consumer-privacy] The data breach was a massive setback for the company and raised several questions about the revelation of the news after two years of the hacking incident.
[src:ccpa-privacy/data-broker] Sources, usually Internet-based since the 1990s, may include census and electoral roll records, social networking sites, court reports and purchase histories.
[src:ccpa-privacy/data-broker] The information from data brokers may be used in background checks used by employers and housing.
[src:ccpa-privacy/data-broker] There are varying regulations around the world limiting the collection of information on individuals; privacy laws vary.
[src:ccpa-privacy/data-broker] In the United States there is no federal regulation protection for the consumer from data brokers, although some states have begun enacting laws individually.
[src:ccpa-privacy/data-broker] In the European Union, GDPR serves to regulate data brokers' operations.
[src:ccpa-privacy/data-broker] Some data brokers report to have large numbers of population data or "data attributes".
[src:ccpa-privacy/data-broker] Acxiom purports to have data from 2.5 billion different people.
[src:ccpa-privacy/data-broker] Credit scores were first used in the 1950s, and information brokering emerged as a career for individuals during that decade.
[src:ccpa-privacy/data-broker] However the business of information brokering did not become widely known or specifically regulated until the 1990s.
[src:ccpa-privacy/data-broker] In 1977, Kelly Warnken published the first fee-based information directory, followed by the *Journal of Fee-Based Information Services* in 1979 and the book *The Information Brokers: How to Start and Operate Your Own Fee-based Service* in 1981.
[src:ccpa-privacy/data-broker] Beginning in the late twentieth century, technological developments such as the development of the Internet, increasing computer processing power, and declining costs of data storage made it much easier for companies to collect, analyze, store and transfer large amounts of data about individuals.
[src:ccpa-privacy/data-broker] This gave rise to the information broker or data broker industry.
[src:ccpa-privacy/data-broker] As of 2021, there is no required academic qualification for the job of information broker; some people may have a bachelor's degree in business or marketing, while others may have a background in library science, or may have worked for a database provider.
[src:ccpa-privacy/data-broker] Information brokering has been described as the "business of buying and selling information as a commodity".
[src:ccpa-privacy/data-broker] Gartner defines an information broker as "a business that aggregates information from a variety of sources; processes it to enrich, cleanse or analyze it; and licenses it to other organizations".
[src:ccpa-privacy/data-broker] It states that data is "licensed for particular or limited uses" rather than sold to a client.
[src:ccpa-privacy/data-broker] Information brokers (IBs) collect and collate data concerning myriad topics, ranging from the daily communications of an individual to more specialized data such as product registrations, patents and copyright data, mostly from publicly available sources, usually obtained from online databases.
[src:ccpa-privacy/data-broker] They may also provide various other services, such as analysing the data and writing reports on them; creating databases for clients; or updating clients whenever new information on a specific topic or person.
[src:ccpa-privacy/data-broker] Clients use data brokers to save themselves time and money, as the brokers are trained in the skills needed to retrieve such information effectively and efficiently.
[src:ccpa-privacy/data-broker] Information brokers are secondary researchers, who find information on a variety of subjects, including companies (often competitors), markets, people, and products.
[src:ccpa-privacy/data-broker] Their role includes analysis and synthesis of the data they find, Brokers may find everything else they can about an individual on the Internet, and aggregate that data with information from a variety of other sources.
[src:ccpa-privacy/data-broker] Information brokers sometimes specialise in a specific area, such as market research, statistics, or scientific data.
[src:ccpa-privacy/data-broker] Clients of information brokers come from a wide range of industries and professions, including manufacturing, financial institutions, political parties, government agencies and historians.
[src:ccpa-privacy/data-broker] Non-profit organizations might benefit from information which helps them to apply for grant funding, and real estate agents often use IBs to undertake land title searches.
[src:ccpa-privacy/data-broker] Advertising, fraud detection and risk mitigation are three common reasons for using data brokers, and these are the three broad categories defined by the Federal Trade Commission.
[src:ccpa-privacy/data-broker] Information brokers need to screen their clients carefully to avoid criminals obtaining data on individuals for nefarious purposes: US broking companies Lexis-Nexis and ChoicePoint have both been duped by phoney clients, leading in one case to identity theft on a large scale.
[src:ccpa-privacy/data-broker] IBs may also purchase information from other companies (such as a credit card company).
[src:ccpa-privacy/data-broker] The information collected may include name, address, social security number, driver's licence number and other such identifying information, as well as occupation, property ownership, income, etc.
[src:ccpa-privacy/data-broker] Advertising companies are most often only interested in profiles and categories rather than personal information about an individual.
[src:ccpa-privacy/data-broker] Information from property records, tax filings, etc. may also be available via "people-search" whitepage sites, either for a small fee or no cost.
[src:ccpa-privacy/data-broker] These websites can thereby have implications for stalking, harassment, and domestic violence.
[src:ccpa-privacy/data-broker] Some datasets may also include geolocation data and is included in marketing resources from Acxiom.
[src:ccpa-privacy/data-broker] Experian and Oracle also advertise location-based marketing services.
[src:ccpa-privacy/data-broker] Many brokers work independently, while others are employees of large companies such as LexisNexis or ProQuest.
[src:ccpa-privacy/data-broker] Data brokers in the United States include Acxiom, Experian, Epsilon, CoreLogic, Datalogix, Intelius, PeekYou, Exactis, and Recorded Future.
[src:ccpa-privacy/data-broker] In 2012, Acxiom claimed to have files on about 500 million active consumers worldwide, with about 1,500 data points per person and, in 2023, Acxiom (renamed LiveRamp) claims to have files on 2.5 billion people and over 3,000 data points per person.
[src:ccpa-privacy/data-broker] The company Oracle has publicly noted it has connections with 80 data broker companies.
[src:ccpa-privacy/data-broker] The US Department of Homeland Security has purchased cell phone location data and home utility data from data brokers to facilitate deportations.
[src:ccpa-privacy/data-broker] The Federal Bureau of Investigation (FBI) has purchased personal data from the company Venntel.
[src:ccpa-privacy/data-broker] Under both of these circumstances, a warrant is not required to acquire this data, due to the fact that it is "open source" or "commercially obtained".
[src:ccpa-privacy/data-broker] Use of the data also has implications in background checks (used in rent/housing and job applications).
[src:ccpa-privacy/data-broker] In 2012, Spokeo, a people search website, settled with the US Federal Trade Commission for $800,000 over violations of the Fair Credit Reporting Act.
[src:ccpa-privacy/data-broker] In 2017, Cambridge Analytica claimed that it has psychological profiles of 220 million United States citizens, based on 5,000 separate data sets, with another source reporting 230 million.
[src:ccpa-privacy/data-broker] A scandal emerged after it was found that after 270,000 Facebook users consented to sharing their data, data was scraped from about 50 million profiles on the social media platform.
[src:ccpa-privacy/data-broker] This was seen as breach of trust by Facebook.
[src:ccpa-privacy/data-broker] In 2018, American companies spent $19 billion acquiring and analyzing consumer data, according to the Interactive Advertising Bureau.
[src:ccpa-privacy/data-broker] In 2021, *The Pillar* outed a Catholic priest by purchasing data from a data broker including data usage from Grindr.
[src:ccpa-privacy/data-broker] Information privacy laws are not as strict in the United States as in the European Union, where data brokers work hard to get around the General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR) regulations, brought into operation in 2018.
[src:ccpa-privacy/data-broker] Under GDPR, data can only be collected for re-use on one of six legal bases.
[src:ccpa-privacy/data-broker] The rather vague term "legitimate interest" is often abused or misinterpreted.
[src:ccpa-privacy/data-broker] Explicit consent from users is required for information storage.
[src:ccpa-privacy/data-broker] In addition, data processing related with political opinion and religious belief is prohibited unless the consent of data subject is granted.
[src:ccpa-privacy/data-broker] In the US, individuals generally cannot find out what data a broker holds on them, how a broker got it, or how it is used.
[src:ccpa-privacy/data-broker] There is no federal law that permits or enables consumers to see, make corrections to, or opt out of data compiled by brokers.
[src:ccpa-privacy/data-broker] Files on individuals are generally sold in lists; examples cited in testimony to the U.S.
[src:ccpa-privacy/data-broker] Congress include lists of rape survivors, seniors with dementia, financially vulnerable people, people with HIV, police officers (by home address), alcoholics, and people with erectile dysfunction.
[src:ccpa-privacy/data-broker] The proposed US Data Accountability and Trust Act (introduced in 2009) contained a number of requirements for auditing and verification of accuracy of data held by information brokers, and additional measures in the case of a security breach.
[src:ccpa-privacy/data-broker] The bill also gave identified individuals the means and opportunity to review and correct the data held that related to them.
[src:ccpa-privacy/data-broker] It passed through the United States House of Representatives in the 111th United States Congress, but failed to pass the United States Senate.
[src:ccpa-privacy/data-broker] It was revived by the 112th United States Congress in 2011 as H.R.
[src:ccpa-privacy/data-broker] 1707., but died after being referred to committee.
[src:ccpa-privacy/data-broker] Federal Trade Commission had recommended the United States Congress develop legislation enabling consumers to see the information that data brokers hold about them, a recommendation it renewed in subsequent reports in 2012 and 2014.
[src:ccpa-privacy/data-broker] Government Accountability Office also called for Congress to consider legislation.
[src:ccpa-privacy/data-broker] In October 2019, California Governor Gavin Newsom signed into action statute AB 1202.
[src:ccpa-privacy/data-broker] This bill "would require data brokers to register with, and provide certain information to, the Attorney General.
[src:ccpa-privacy/data-broker] The bill would define a data broker as a business that knowingly collects and sells to third parties the personal information of a consumer with whom the business does not have a direct relationship, subject to specified exceptions".
[src:ccpa-privacy/data-broker] This law was created to safeguard against the "cloak of invisibility" (unregistered, unregulated, untracked information broker) that previous data brokers roamed in.
[src:ccpa-privacy/data-broker] It was also meant to regulate the purchasing of data in commercial third party buyers, and tracks the data brokers information trades.
[src:ccpa-privacy/data-broker] Due to the interest in federal regulation, data broker firms have lobbied and spent $29 million in the year 2020.
[src:ccpa-privacy/data-broker] In 2025, Zhou Shuai and Yin Kecheng, two China-based data brokers wanted by the FBI were accused by the United States Department of State of selling sensitive American data to China’s Ministry of Public Security (MPS).
[src:ccpa-privacy/data-broker] A United States Senate Committee in 2013 published *A Review of the Data Broker Industry: Collection, Use, and Sale of Consumer Data for Marketing Purposes*.
[src:ccpa-privacy/data-broker] The information produced by data brokers has been criticized for enabling discrimination in pricing, services and opportunities.
[src:ccpa-privacy/data-broker] For example, a May 2014 White House report found that web searches that included black-seeming first names such as Jermaine were more likely to result in ads being displayed that include the word "arrest," compared with web searches including white-seeming first names such as Geoffrey.
[src:ccpa-privacy/data-broker] An Online Information Broker FAQ is published by Privacy Rights Clearinghouse (PRC), a nonprofit consumer organization in the United States.
[src:ccpa-privacy/data-broker] PRC also maintains a list of information brokers, with links to their privacy policies, terms of service, and opt-out provisions.
[src:ccpa-privacy/data-broker] Data brokers have also faced legal charges for security breaches due to poor data security practices.
[src:ccpa-privacy/data-broker] The Association of Independent Information Professionals (AIIP) is a professional association based in Baton Rouge, Louisiana, with members from 20 countries worldwide, representing both primary and secondary researchers.
[src:ccpa-privacy/data-broker] Examples of information brokers in contemporary fiction would be the Shadow Broker in the video game series *Mass Effect*; Nicholas Wayne, Rachel, Elean Duga, Gustav St.
[src:ccpa-privacy/data-broker] Germain, Carol, and the President of the Daily Days newspaper company in *Baccano!*; or Izaya Orihara in the light novel series *Durarara!!*.
[src:ccpa-privacy/data-broker] A few of the characters in Neal Stephenson's novel Snow Crash find work selling data as "stringers" for the Central Intelligence Corporation.
[src:ccpa-privacy/data-broker] Information broker characters play a prominent role in stories published by DC Comics.
[src:ccpa-privacy/data-broker] The character trope is prominently used by the superhero Oracle, as well as Calculator, Proxy, and Chloe Sullivan.
[src:ccpa-privacy/data-broker] In the Arrowverse, Felicity Smoak is depicted as a data broker.
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] Over 80 countries and independent territories, including nearly every country in Europe and many in Latin America and the Caribbean, Asia, and Africa, have now adopted comprehensive data protection laws.
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] The European Union has the General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR), in force since May 25, 2018.
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] The United States is notable for not having adopted a comprehensive information privacy law, but rather having adopted limited sectoral laws in some areas like the California Consumer Privacy Act (CCPA).
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] The German state of Hessia enacted the world's first data privacy law on September 30, 1970.
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] In Germany the term **informational self-determination** was first used in the context of a German constitutional ruling relating to personal information collected during the 1983 census.
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] India passed its Digital Personal Data Protection Act, 2023 in August 2023.
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] China passed its Personal Information Protection Law (PIPL) in mid-2021, and was effective from November 1, 2021.
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] It focuses heavily on consent, rights of the individual, and transparency of data processing.
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] PIPL has been compared to the EU GDPR as it has similar scope and many similar provisions.
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] In the Philippines, The Data Privacy Act of 2012 mandated the creation of the National Privacy Commission that would monitor and maintain policies that involve information privacy and personal data protection in the country.
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] Modeled after the EU Data Protection Directive and the Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation (APEC) Privacy Framework, the independent body would ensure compliance of the country with international standards set for data protection.
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] Personal information must be handled properly.
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] Information must be kept accurate and relevant, used only for the stated purposes, and retained only for as long as reasonably needed.
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] The law required entities to be active in ensuring that unauthorized parties do not have access to their customers' information.
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] Personal information must be disposed in way that unauthorized third parties could not access the discarded data.
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] In early 2022, Sri Lanka became the first country in South Asia to enact comprehensive data privacy legislation.
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] 9 of 2022, effective since March 19, 2022, applies to processing within Sri Lanka and extends extraterritorially to controllers or processors offering goods and services to individuals in Sri Lanka and/or monitoring their behavior in the country.
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] The right to data privacy is relatively heavily regulated and actively enforced in Europe.
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] Article 8 of the European Convention on Human Rights (ECHR) provides a right to respect for one's *"private and family life, his home and his correspondence"*, subject to certain restrictions.
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] The European Court of Human Rights has given this article a very broad interpretation in its jurisprudence.
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] According to the Court's case law the collection of information by officials of the state about an individual without their consent always falls within the scope of Article 8.
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] Thus, gathering information for the official census, recording fingerprints and photographs in a police register, collecting medical data or details of personal expenditures, and implementing a system of personal identification has been judged to raise data privacy issues.
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] What also falls under "privacy-sensitive data" under the GDPR is such information as racial or ethnic origin, political opinions, religious or philosophical beliefs and information regarding a person's sex life or sexual orientation.
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] The government is not the only entity which may pose a threat to data privacy.
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] Other citizens, and private companies most importantly, may also engage in threatening activities, especially since the automated processing of data became widespread.
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] The Convention for the Protection of Individuals with regard to Automatic Processing of Personal Data was concluded within the Council of Europe in 1981.
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] This convention obliges the signatories to enact legislation concerning the automatic processing of personal data, which many duly did.
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] Therefore, the European Commission decided to propose harmonizing data protection law within the EU.
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] The resulting Data Protection Directive was adopted by the European Parliament and ministers from national governments in 1995 and had to be transposed into national law by the end of 1998.
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] The directive contains a number of key principles with which member states must comply.
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] Anyone processing personal data must comply with the eight enforceable principles of good practice.
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] Processed in accordance with the data subject's rights.
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] Transferred only to countries with adequate protection.
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] Personal data covers both facts and opinions about the individual.
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] It also includes information regarding the intentions of the data controller towards the individual, although in some limited circumstances exemptions will apply.
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] With processing, the definition is far wider than before.
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] For example, it incorporates the concepts of "obtaining", "holding" and "disclosing".
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] All EU member states adopted legislation pursuant this directive or adapted their existing laws.
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] Each country also has its own supervisory authority to monitor the level of protection.
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] Because of this, in theory the transfer of personal information from the EU to the US is prohibited when equivalent privacy protection is not in place in the US.
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] American companies that would work with EU data must comply with the Safe Harbour Archived 2010-06-09 at the Wayback Machine framework.
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] The core principles of data protected are limited collection, consent of the subject, accuracy, integrity, security, subject right of review and deletion.
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] As a result, customers of international organizations such as Amazon and eBay in the EU have the ability to review and delete information, while Americans do not.
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] In the United States the equivalent guiding philosophy is the Code of Fair Information Practice (FIP).
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] The difference in language here is important: in the United States the debate is about privacy where in the European Community the debate is on data protection.
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] Moving the debate from privacy to data protection is seen by some philosophers as a mechanism for moving forward in the practical realm while not requiring agreement on fundamental questions about the nature of privacy.
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] 78-17 of 6 January 1978 concerning information technology, files and civil liberties"*.
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] In Germany, both the federal government and the states enacted legislation.
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] However, Swiss law imposes less restrictions upon data processing than the Directive in several respects.
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] In Switzerland, the right to privacy is guaranteed in article 13 of the Swiss Federal Constitution.
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] The Swiss Federal Data Protection Act (DPA) and the Swiss Federal Data Protection Ordinance (DPO) entered into force on July 1, 1993.
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] The latest amendments of the DPA and the DPO entered into force on January 1, 2008.
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] The DPA applies to the processing of personal data by private persons and federal government agencies.
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] Unlike the data protection legislation of many other countries, the DPA protects both personal data pertaining to natural persons and legal entities.
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] The Swiss Federal Data Protection and Information Commissioner in particular supervises compliance of the federal government agencies with the DPA, provides advice to private persons on data protection, conducts investigations and makes recommendations concerning data protection practices.
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] Some data files must be registered with the Swiss Federal Data Protection and Information Commissioner before they are created.
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] In the case of a transfer of personal data outside of Switzerland, special requirements need to be met and, depending on the circumstances, the Swiss Federal Data Protection and Information Commissioner must be informed before the transfer is made.
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] Most Swiss cantons have enacted their own data protection laws regulating the processing of personal data by cantonal and municipal bodies.
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] In the United Kingdom the Data Protection Act 1998 (c 29) (Information Commissioner) implemented the EU Directive on the protection of personal data .
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] It replaced the Data Protection Act 1984 (c 35).
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] The 2016 General Data Protection Regulation supersedes previous Protection Acts.
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] The Data Protection Act 2018 (c 12) updates data protection laws in the UK.
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] It is a national law which complements the European Union's General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR).
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] In Canada, the Personal Information Protection and Electronic Documents Act (PIPEDA) went into effect on 1 January 2001, applicable to private bodies which are federally regulated.
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] All other organizations were included on 1 January 2004.
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] The PIPEDA brought Canada into compliance with EU data protection law, although civil society, regulators, and academics have claimed that it does not address modern challenges of privacy law as well as the GDPR does, calling for reform.
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] The PIPEDA specifies the rules to govern collection, use, or disclosure of the personal information in the course of recognizing the right of privacy of individuals with respect to their personal information.
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] It also specifies the rules for the organizations to collect, use, and disclose personal information.
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] The organizations and the employee of the organization collect, use, or discloses in the course of operation of a federal work, undertaking, or business.
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] Individuals who collect, use, or disclose personal information for personal purpose and use.
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] Organizations which collect, use, or disclose personal information only for journalistic, artistic or literary purposes.
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] "Personal Information" means information about an identifiable individual, but does not include the name, title, or business address or telephone number of an employee of an organization.
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] "Organization" means an association, a partnership, a person and a trade union.
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] 10. a work, undertaking or business to which federal laws, within the meaning of section 2 of the Oceans Act, apply under section 20 of that Act and any regulations made under paragraph 26(1)(k) of that Act.
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] 2. expect organizations to collect, use or disclose personal information in a reasonable and appropriate way.
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] 3. understand who in the organizations pays the responsibility for protecting individuals' personal information.
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] 4. expect organizations to protect the personal information in a reasonable and secure way.
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] 5. expect the personal information held by the organizations to be accurate, complete, and up-to-date.
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] 6. have the access to their personal information and ask for any corrections or have the right to make complain towards the organizations.
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] 2. collect personal information in a reasonable, appropriate, and lawful ways.
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] 3. establish personal information policies that are clear, reasonable, and ready to protect individuals' person information.
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] Data privacy is not highly legislated or regulated in the U.S.
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] In the United States, access to private data contained in, for example, third-party credit reports may be sought when seeking employment or medical care, or making automobile, housing, or other purchases on credit terms.
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] Although partial regulations exist, there is no all-encompassing law regulating the acquisition, storage, or use of personal data in the U.S.
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] The Supreme Court interpreted the Constitution to grant a right of privacy to individuals in *Griswold v.
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] Very few states, however, recognize an individual's right to privacy, a notable exception being California.
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] An inalienable right to privacy is enshrined in the California Constitution's article 1, section 1, and the California legislature has enacted several pieces of legislation aimed at protecting this right.
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] The California Online Privacy Protection Act (OPPA) of 2003 requires operators of commercial web sites or online services that collect personal information on California residents through a web site to conspicuously post a privacy policy on the site and to comply with its policy.
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] The safe harbor arrangement was developed by the United States Department of Commerce in order to provide a means for U.S. companies to demonstrate compliance with European Commission directives and thus to simplify relations between them and European businesses.
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] The Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act (HIPAA) was enacted by the U.S.
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] HIPAA is also known as the Kennedy-Kassebaum Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act (HIPAA-Public Law 104-191), effective August 21, 1996.
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] One difficulty with HIPAA is that there must be a mechanism to authenticate the patient who demands access to his/her data.
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] As a result, medical facilities have begun to ask for Social Security Numbers from patients, thus arguably decreasing privacy by simplifying the act of correlating health records with other records.
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] The issue of consent is problematic under HIPAA, because the medical providers simply make care contingent upon agreeing to the privacy standards in practice.
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] The Fair Credit Reporting Act applies the principles of the Code of Fair Information Practice to credit reporting agencies.
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] Because of the Fair and Accurate Credit Transactions Act, each person can obtain a free annual credit report.
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] The Fair Credit Reporting Act has been effective in preventing the proliferation of specious so-called private credit guides.
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] Before 1970, private credit guides offered detailed, if unreliable, information on easily identifiable individuals.
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] Before the Fair Credit Reporting Act, salacious unsubstantiated material could be included – and in fact, gossip was widely included in credit reports.
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] The Consumer Data Industry Association, which represents the consumer reporting industry, also has a website with FCRA information.
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] The Fair Credit Reporting Act provides consumers the ability to view, correct, contest, and limit the uses of credit reports.
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] The FCRA also protects the credit agency from the charge of negligent release in the case of misrepresentation by the requester.
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] Credit agencies must ask the requester the purpose of a requested information release, but need to make no effort to verify the truth of the requester's assertions.
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] In fact, the courts have ruled that, "The Act clearly does not provide a remedy for an illicit or abusive use of information about consumers" (Henry v Forbes, 1976).
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] It is widely believed that in order to avoid the FCRA, ChoicePoint was created by Equifax at which time the parent company copied all its records to its newly created subsidiary.
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] ChoicePoint is not a credit reporting agency, and thus FCRA does not apply.
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] The Fair Debt Collection Practices Act similarly limits dissemination of information about a consumer's financial transactions.
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] It prevents creditors or their agents from disclosing the fact that an individual is in debt to a third party, although it allows creditors and their agents to attempt to obtain information about a debtor's location.
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] It limits the actions of those seeking payment of a debt.
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] For example, debt collection agencies are prohibited from harassment or contacting individuals at work.
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] The Bankruptcy Abuse Prevention and Consumer Protection Act of 2005 (which actually gutted consumer protections, for example in case of bankruptcy resulting from medical cost) limited some of these controls on debtors.
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] The Electronic Communications Privacy Act (ECPA) establishes criminal sanctions for interception of electronic communication.
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] However, the legislation has been criticized for lack of impact due to loopholes.
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] Several US federal agencies have privacy statutes that cover their collection and use of private information.
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] These include the Census Bureau, the Internal Revenue Service, and the National Center for Education Statistics (under the Education Sciences Reform Act).
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] In addition, the CIPSEA statute protects confidentiality of data collected by federal statistical agencies.
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] Lawmakers in several states have proposed legislation to change the way online businesses handle user information.
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] Among those generating significant attention are several Do Not Track legislation and the Right to Know Act (California Bill AB 1291).
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] The California Right to Know Act, if passed, would require every business which keeps user information to provide its user a copy of stored information when requested.
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] The bill faced heavy oppositions from trade groups representing companies such as Google, Microsoft, and Facebook, and failed to pass.
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] Arkansas has a biometric data privacy law.
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] On June 28, 2018 California legislature passed AB 375, the California Consumer Privacy Act of 2018, effective January 1, 2020.
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] In November 2020, Proposition 24, also known as the California Privacy Rights Act, amended and expanded the CCPA.
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] The law specifically protects employee data.
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] On June 6, 2023, Florida enacted Florida Senate Bill 262, effective July 1, 2024.
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] It gives consumers the right to confirm whether businesses with over $1 billion in gross annual revenue who derive more than half of their revenue from online ads collected data about them and control over the data, including correction and deletion.
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] The law also prohibits government agencies from asking a social media companies to censor content or remove users from its platform.
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] On October 3, 2008, Illinois enacted the Biometric Information Privacy Act.
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] The law was the first in the nation to regulate biometric data.
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] The law requires private businesses to obtain consent to collect or disclose the biometric identifiers of consumers.
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] The law also requires the data be securely stored and destroyed in a timely manner.
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] In 2021, New York enacted a commercial biometric data privacy law that requires businesses to conspicuously notify consumers of data collection.
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] The law bars employers from collecting biometric data from employees.
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] In 2009, Texas enacted a consumer law requiring consent for biometric data for commercial use to be leased, sold, or disclosed.
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] The law also requires the data be destroyed within one year of collection.
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] In 2017, Washington enacted a specific consumer biometric data privacy law covering commercial use.
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] On April 27, 2023, Washington enacted the My Health, My Data Act, effective March 31, 2024.
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] The law was the first in the nation to regulate consumer health data not protected by HIPAA.
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] The law requires companies to obtain prior authorization to obtain, share, or sell health data, including data that can be used to infer or linked to health status, such as purchasing medications or digestion tracking.
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] The law guarantees the right to withdraw consent and request deletion.
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] The law also prohibits geo-fences around healthcare facilities.
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] Brazil's General Personal Data Protection Law (LGPD) became law on September 18, 2020.
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] The law's primary aim is to unify 40 different Brazilian laws that regulate the processing of personal data.
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] The bill has 65 articles and has many similarities to the GDPR.
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] Unlike the U.S. approach to privacy protection, which relies on industry-specific legislation, regulation and self-regulation, the European Union relies on the comprehensive privacy legislation.
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] The European Directive on Data Protection that went into effect in October 1998, includes, for example, the requirement to create government data protection agencies, registration of databases with those agencies, and in some instances prior approval before personal data processing may begin.
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] In order to bridge these different privacy approaches and provide a streamlined means for U.S. organizations to comply with the Directive, the U.S.
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] Department of Commerce in consultation with the European Commission developed a "safe harbor" framework.
[src:ccpa-privacy/information-privacy-law] In order for the framework to be enforced, companies must publicly publish a privacy policy.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p01] Laws related to privacy may deal with information privacy, bodily or physical privacy (related to bodily integrity), privacy of the home and property, privacy of communications (secrecy of correspondence), and privacy of thought (related to intellectual freedom).
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p01] Information privacy laws govern the collection, storage, and use of personal information by governments, companies, organizations, and individuals.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p01] These laws protect personal and confidential details, including names, addresses, and contact information, as well as sensitive data such as health records (medical privacy) and financial information.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p01] Privacy laws have evolved to address emerging challenges, with significant milestones including the Privacy Act of 1974 in the U.S. and the European Union's Data Protection Directive of 1995.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p01] Today, international standards like the GDPR set global benchmarks, while sector-specific regulations like HIPAA and COPPA complement state-level laws in the U.S.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p01] In Canada, PIPEDA governs privacy, with recent case law shaping privacy rights.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p01] Digital platform challenges underscore the ongoing evolution and compliance complexities in privacy law.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p01] A challenging issue is handling aerial drone technology within privacy laws.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p01] The Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation (APEC) introduced a voluntary Privacy Framework in 2004, which all 21 member economies adopted.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p01] This framework aims to enhance general information privacy and facilitate the secure transfer of data across borders.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p01] In 2011, APEC established the APEC Cross Border Privacy Rules System to balance the flow of information and data across borders, which is crucial for fostering trust and confidence in the online marketplace.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p01] This system builds upon the APEC Privacy Framework and incorporates four agreed-upon rules, which involve self-assessment, compliance review, recognition/acceptance, and dispute resolution and enforcement.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p01] Article 8 of the European Convention on Human Rights, established by the Council of Europe in 1950 and applicable across the European continent except for Belarus and Kosovo, safeguards the right to privacy.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p01] It asserts that "Everyone has the right to respect for his private and family life, his home and his correspondence." Through extensive case law from the European Court of Human Rights in Strasbourg, privacy has been clearly defined and universally recognized as a fundamental right.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p01] Furthermore, the Council of Europe took steps to protect individuals' privacy rights with specific measures.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p01] In 1981, it adopted the Convention for the protection of individuals with regard to automatic processing of personal data.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p01] Additionally, in 1998, the Council addressed privacy concerns related to the internet by publishing "Draft Guidelines for the protection of individuals with regard to the collection and processing of personal data on the information highway," developed in collaboration with the European Commission.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p01] These guidelines were formally adopted in 1999.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p01] The 1995 Data Protection Directive (officially Directive 95/46/EC) acknowledged the authority of national data protection authorities and mandated that all Member States adhere to standardized privacy protection guidelines.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p01] These guidelines stipulated that Member States must enact stringent privacy laws consistent with the framework provided by the Directive.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p01] Moreover, the Directive specified that non-EU countries must implement privacy legislation of equivalent rigor to exchange personal data with EU countries.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p01] Additionally, companies in non-EU countries wishing to conduct business with EU-based companies must adhere to privacy standards at least as strict as those outlined in the Directive.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p01] Consequently, the Directive has influenced the development of privacy legislation beyond European borders.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p01] The proposed ePrivacy Regulation, intended to replace the Privacy and Electronic Communications Directive 2002, further contributes to EU privacy regulations.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p01] On 25 May 2018, the General Data Protection Regulation superseded the Data Protection Directive of 1995.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p01] A significant aspect introduced by the General Data Protection Regulation is the recognition of the "right to be forgotten," which mandates that any organization collecting data on individuals must delete the relevant data upon the individual's request.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p01] The Regulation drew inspiration from the European Convention on Human Rights mentioned earlier.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p01] The OECD (Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development) initiated privacy guidelines in 1980, setting international standards, and in 2007, proposed cross-border cooperation for privacy law enforcement.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p01] The UN's International Covenant on Civil and Political Rights, Article 17, protects privacy, echoed in the 2013 UN General Assembly resolution affirming privacy as a fundamental human right in the digital age.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p01] The Principles on Personal Data Protection and Privacy for the UN System were declared in 2018.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p01] Article 17 of the International Covenant on Civil and Political Rights of the United Nations in 1966 also protects privacy: "No one shall be subjected to arbitrary or unlawful interference with his privacy, family, home or correspondence, nor to unlawful attacks on his honor and reputation.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p01] On 18 December 2013, the United Nations General Assembly adopted resolution 68/167 on the right to privacy in the digital age.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p01] The resolution makes reference to the Universal Declaration of Human Rights and reaffirms the fundamental and protected human right of privacy.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p01] The Principles on Personal Data Protection and Privacy for the United Nations System were declared on 11 October 2018.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] There are many privacy laws widely arranged in different countries, reflecting legal traditions and policy priorities on how confidential data should be protected.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] Many of these laws focus as well on the protection of personal and confidential data by individuals and the transparency of data.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] The current state of privacy law in Australia includes Federal and state information privacy legislation, some sector-specific privacy legislation at state level, regulation of the media and some criminal sanctions.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] The current position concerning civil causes of action for invasion of privacy is unclear: some courts have indicated that a tort of invasion of privacy may exist in Australia.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] However this has not been upheld by the higher courts, which have been content to develop the equitable doctrine of Breach of Confidence to protect privacy, following the example set by the UK.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] In 2008, the Australian Law Reform Commission recommended the enactment of a statutory cause of action for invasion of privacy.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] The Privacy Act 1988 aims to protect and regulate an individual's private information.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] It manages and monitors Australian Government and organisations on how they hold personal information.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] The Bahamas has an official data protection law that protects the personal information of its citizens in both the private and public sector: Data Protection Act 2003 (the Bahamas Law).
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] The Bahamas Law appoints a data protection commissioner to the Office of Data Protection to ensure that data protection is being held.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] Also, there are no requirements for registering databases or restricting data flow across national borders.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] Therefore, the legislation does not meet European Union standards, which was the goal of creating the law in the first place.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] Belize has an official privacy act which is the Data Protection Act (2021).
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] This act regulates the usage and collection of personal data to protect individual privacy.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] This act establishes different data protection principles and data subjects.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] Additionally, the Freedom of Information Act currently protects the personal information of the citizens of Belize.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] The Freedom of Information Act became effective in 1967 and is a federal law that grants any individual to access records from federal government agencies.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] The FOIA grants public access to businesses and organizations to be able to access federal records, but does not provide access to federal records held from the United States.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] On 14 August 2018, Brazil enacted its General Personal Data Protection Law.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] The first translation into English of the new data protection law was published by Ronaldo Lemos, a Brazilian lawyer specialized in technology, on that same date.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] In Canada, the federal *Personal Information Protection and Electronic Documents Act* (PIPEDA) governs the collection, use, and disclosure of personal information in connection with commercial activities, as well as personal information about employees of federal works, undertakings and businesses.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] The PIPEDA brings Canada into compliance with EU data protection law, although civil society, regulators, and academics have more recently claimed that it does not address modern challenges of privacy law sufficiently, particularly in view of AI, calling for reform.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] PIPEDA does not apply to non-commercial organizations or provincial governments, which remain within the jurisdiction of provinces.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] Five Canadian provinces have enacted privacy laws that apply to their private sector.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] Personal information collected, used and disclosed by the federal government and crown corporations is governed by the *Privacy Act*.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] Many provinces have enacted provincial legislation similar to the Privacy Act, such as the Ontario *Freedom of Information and Protection of Privacy Act* which applies to public bodies in that province.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] There remains some debate whether there exists a common law tort for breach of privacy across Canada.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] There have been a number of cases identifying a common law right to privacy but the requirements have not always been articulated clearly.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] Canadian privacy laws have significant implications for various sectors, particularly finance, healthcare, and digital commerce.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] For instance, the financial sector is strictly regulated under PIPEDA, which requires financial institutions to obtain consent for the collection, use, or disclosure of personal information.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] Moreover, these institutions must also provide robust safeguards to protect this information against loss or theft.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] In healthcare, provinces like Alberta and British Columbia have specific laws protecting personal health information, which require healthcare providers to manage patient data with high confidentiality and security levels.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] This includes ensuring that patient consent is obtained before their personal health information is shared or accessed.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] Recent case law in Canada has further defined the scope and application of privacy laws.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] Tsige* recognized the tort of intrusion upon seclusion, affirming that individuals have a right to privacy against unreasonable intrusion.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] This landmark ruling has significant implications for how personal data is handled across all sectors, emphasizing the need for businesses to maintain strict privacy controls.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] Canadian privacy laws also interact with international frameworks, notably the European Union's General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR).
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] Although PIPEDA shares many similarities with GDPR, there are nuanced differences, particularly in terms of consent and data subject rights.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] The digital transformation has brought specific challenges and focus areas for privacy regulation in Canada.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] The Canadian Anti-Spam Legislation (CASL), for example, regulates how businesses can conduct digital marketing and communications, requiring explicit consent for sending commercial electronic messages.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] This legislation is part of Canada's efforts to protect consumers from spam and related threats while ensuring that businesses conduct their digital marketing responsibly.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] The rise of digital platforms has also prompted discussions about privacy rights concerning consumer data collected by large tech companies.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] Canadian privacy laws are continually evolving to address new challenges posed by technological advancements and global data flows.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] Businesses operating in Canada must stay informed about these changes to ensure compliance and protect the personal information of their customers effectively.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] For detailed guidance and the latest updates on compliance with Canadian privacy laws, businesses and individuals can refer to resources provided by the Office of the Privacy Commissioner of Canada and stay informed about developments in Canadian privacy law through expert analyses and updates.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] In 1995, the Computer Processed Personal Information Protection Act was enacted in order to protect personal information processed by computers.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] The general provision specified the purpose of the law, defined crucial terms, prohibited individuals from waiving certain rights.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] An archipelago located in the Pacific, the country of Fiji was founded on 10 October 1970.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] In its constitution, the people inhabiting the land are granted the right to privacy.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] The exact workings from the constitution is the following: "Every person has the right to personal privacy, which includes the right to — (a) confidentiality of their personal information; (b) confidentiality of their communications; and (c) respect for their private and family life".
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] But in this very same constitution, it is expressed that it is possible "to the extent that it is necessary" for a law to be passed that limits or impacts the execution of the right to privacy law.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] Another privacy related law can be seen in section 54 of the Telecommunications Promulgation passed in 2008, which states that "any service provider supplying telecommunications to consumers must keep information about consumers confidential".
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] Billing information and call information are no exceptions.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] The only exception to this rule is for the purpose of bringing to light "fraud or bad debt".
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] Under this law, even with the consent of the customer, the disclosure of information is not permitted.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] Other Privacy laws that have been adopted by this country are those that are meant to protect the collected information, cookies and other privacy-related matter of tourist.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] This is in regards to (but not limited to) information collected during bookings, the use of one technology of another that belongs to said company or through the use of a service of the company, or when making payments.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] Additionally, as a member of the United Nations, the Fiji is bound by the Universal Declaration of Human Rights which states in article twelve, "No one shall be subjected to arbitrary interference with his privacy, family, home or correspondence, nor to attacks upon his honor and reputation.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] Everyone has the right to the protection of the law against such interference or attacks".
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] France adopted a data privacy law in 1978.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] It applies to public and private organizations and forbids gathering sensitive data about physical persons (including sexuality, ethnicity, and political or religious opinions).
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] The law is administered by the Commission nationale de l'informatique et des libertés (CNIL), a dedicated national administration.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] Like in Germany, data violations are considered criminal offenses (Art.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] 84 GPR with Code Pénal, Section 1, Chapitre VI, Art.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] Germany is known to be one of the first countries (in 1970) with the strictest and most detailed data privacy laws in the world.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] The citizens' right to protection is stated in the Constitution of Germany, in Art.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] The citizens' data of Germany is mainly protected under the Federal Data Protection Act (1977) from corporations, which has been amended the most recently in 2009.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] This act specifically targets all businesses that collect information for its use.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] The major regulation protects the data within the private and personal sector, and as a member of the European Union (EU), Germany has additionally ratified its act, convention, and additional protocol with the EU according to the EU Data Protection Directive 95/46 EC.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] In Germany, there are two kinds of restrictions on a transfer of personal data.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] Since Germany is part of the EU Member States, the transfer of personal data of its citizens to a nation outside the EEA is always subject to a decent level of data protection in the offshore country.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] Secondly, according to German data policy rules, any transfer of personal data outside the EEA symbolizes a connection to a third party which requires a reason.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] That reason may be for emergency reasons, and a provision must be met with consent by the receiver and the subject of the data.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] Keep in mind that in Germany, data transfers within a group of companies is subject to the same treatment as transfer to third-parties if the location is outside the EEA.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] Specifically, the Federal Data Protection Commission is in charge of regulating the entirety of the enforcement of data privacy regulations for Germany.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] In addition, Germany is part of the Organisation for Economic Cooperation and Development (OECD).
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] The Federal Data Protection Commission of Germany is a member of the International Conference of Data Protection and Privacy Commissioners, European Data Protection Authorities, the EU Article 29 Working Party, and the Global Privacy Enforcement Network.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] Regarding the protection of children, Germany is potentially the first nation that has played an active role in banning the share of data within toys connected to Wi-Fi and the Internet, like for instance, "My Friend Cayla".
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] The group in charge of protecting the data of children is the Federal Network Agency (*Bundesnetzagentur*).
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] Like in France, data violations are considered offenses (Art.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] During the military dictatorship era the 57 AK law prohibited taking photos of people without their permission but the law has since been superseded.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] However, photographing people or collecting their personal data for commercial (advertising) purposes requires their consent.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] In Greece the right to take photographs and publish them or sell licensing rights over them as fine art or editorial content is protected by the Constitution of Greece (Article 14 and other articles) and free speech laws as well as by case law and legal cases.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] Photographing the police or children and publishing the photographs in a non-commercial capacity is also legal.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] In Hong Kong, the law governing the protection of personal data is principally found in the Personal Data (Privacy) Ordinance (Cap.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] 486) which came into force on 20 December 1996.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] Various amendments were made to enhance the protection of personal data privacy of individuals through the Personal Data (Privacy) (Amendment) Ordinance 2012.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] Examples of personal data protected include names, phone numbers, addresses, identity card numbers, photos, medical records and employment records.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] As Hong Kong remains a common law jurisdiction, judicial cases are also a source of privacy law.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] The power of enforcement is vested with the Privacy Commissioner (the "Commissioner") for Personal Data.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] Non-compliance with data protection principles set out in the ordinances does not constitute a criminal offense directly.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] The Commissioner may serve an enforcement notice to direct the data user to remedy the contravention and/or instigate the prosecution action.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] Contravention of an enforcement notice may result in a fine and imprisonment.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] India's data protection law is known as The Digital Personal Data Protection Act, 2023, the Right to Privacy is a fundamental right and an intrinsic part of Article 21 that protects life and liberty of the citizens and as a part of the freedoms guaranteed by Part III of the Constitution.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] In June 2011, India passed subordinate legislation that included various new rules that apply to companies and consumers.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] A key aspect of the new rules required that any organization that processes personal information must obtain written consent from the data subjects before undertaking certain activities.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] However, application and enforcement of the rules is still uncertain.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] The Aadhaar Card privacy issue became controversial when the case reached the Supreme Court.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] The hearing in the Aadhaar case went on for 38 days across 4 months, making it the second longest Supreme Court hearing after the landmark Kesavananda Bharati v.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] On 24 August 2017, a nine-judge bench of the Supreme Court in Justice K.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] Puttaswamy (Retd.) and Anr. vs Union Of India And Ors. unanimously held that the right to privacy is an intrinsic part of right to life and personal liberty under Article 21 of the Constitution.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] Ireland is under the Data Protection Act 1988 along with the EU General Data Protection Regulation, which regulates the utilization of personal data.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] The DPA protects data within the private and personal sector.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] The DPA ensures that when data is transported, the location must be safe and in acknowledgement of the legislation to maintain data privacy.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] Specifically the Data Protection Commissioner oversees the entirety of the enforcement of data privacy regulations for Ireland.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] All persons that collect and process data must register with the Data Protection Commissioner unless they are exempt (non-profit organizations, journalistic, academic, literary expression etc.) and renew their registration annually.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] Considering the protection of internet property and online data, the ePrivacy Regulations 2011 protect the communications and higher-advanced technical property and data such as social media and the telephone.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] In relation to international data privacy law that Ireland is involved in, the British–Irish Agreement Act 1999 Section 51 extensively states the relationship between data security between the United Kingdom and Ireland.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] In addition, Ireland is part of the Council of Europe and the Organisation for Economic Cooperation and Development.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] Ireland is also the main international location for social media platforms, specifically LinkedIn and Twitter, for data collection and control for any data processed outside the United States.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] In the Israel privacy law, infringement of privacy is a civil wrong and many types of it constitute an offense punishable by up to 5 years of imprisonment.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] A considerable part of this law considers privacy of databases and their use for mailing.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] The Jamaican constitution grants its people the right to "respect for and protection of private and family life, and privacy of the home".
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] Although the government grants its citizens the right to privacy, the protection of this right is not strong.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] But in regards to other privacy laws that have been adopted in Jamaica, the closest one is the Private Security Regulation Authority Act.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] This act passed in the year 1992, establishing the Private Security Regulation Authority.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] This organization is tasked with the responsibility of regulating the private security business and ensuring that everyone working as a private security guard is trained and certified.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] The goal of this is to ensure a safer home, community, and businesses.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] Additionally, as a member of the United Nations, the Jamaica is bound by the Universal Declaration of Human Rights which states in article two "No one shall be subjected to arbitrary interference with his privacy, family, home or correspondence, nor to attacks upon his honor and reputation.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] The two latter acts (amended in 2016) contain provisions applicable to the protection of personal information by public sector entities.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] Kenya currently does not have a strong general privacy protection law for its constituents.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] But in chapter 4 — The Bill of Rights, and in the second part which is titled "Rights and Fundamental Freedoms", of the constitution, privacy is allocated its own section.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] Although Kenya grants its people the right to privacy, there seems to be no existing document that protects these specific privacy laws.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] Regarding privacy laws relating to data privacy, like many African countries as expressed by Alex Boniface Makulilo, Kenya's privacy laws are far from the European 'adequacy' standard.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] As of today, Kenya does have laws that focus on specific sectors.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] The following are the sectors: communication and information.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] The law pertaining to this is called the Kenya Information and Communication Act.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] This Act makes it illegal for any licensed telecommunication operators to disclose or intercept information that is able to get access through the customer's use of the service.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] This law also grants privacy protection in the course of making use of the service provided by said company.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] And if the information of the customer is going to be provided to any third party it is mandatory that the customer is made aware of such an exchange and that some form of agreement is reached, even if the person is a family member.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] This act also goes as far as protecting data for Kenyans especially for the use of fraud and other ill manners.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] Additionally, as a member of the United Nations, Kenya is bound by the universal declaration of Human Rights which states in article two "No one shall be subjected to arbitrary interference with his privacy, family, home or correspondence, nor to attacks upon his honor and reputation.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] After their independence from Great Britain in 1957, Malaysia's existing legal system was based primarily on English common law.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] The following common law torts are related to personal information privacy and continue to play a role in Malaysia's legal system: breach of confidence, defamation, malicious falsehood, and negligence.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] In recent years, however, the Court of Appeal in Malaysia has referred less to English common law and instead looked more toward other nations with similar colonial histories and whose written constitutions are more like the Malaysian Constitution.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] Unlike the courts in these other nations, such as India's Supreme Court, the Malaysian Court of Appeal has not yet recognized a constitutionally protected right to privacy.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] In June 2010, the Malaysian Parliament passed the Personal Data Protection Act 2010, and it came into effect in 2013.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] It outlines seven Personal Data Protection Principles that entities operating in Malaysia must adhere to: the General Principle, the Notice and Choice Principle, the Disclosure Principle, the Security Principle, the Retention Principle, the Data Integrity Principle, and the Access Principle.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] A notable contribution to general privacy law is the Act's distinction between personal data and sensitive personal data, which entails different protections.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] On 5 July 2010, Mexico enacted a new privacy package, the Federal Law on Protection of Personal Data Held by Individuals, focused on treatment of personal data by private entities.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] A Data Protection legislation was enacted in 2017 and it took effect in 2018.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] The objective of the legislation was to strengthen the control and personal autonomy of a person over their personal data, in line.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] The law is generally invoked to settle disputes between neighbors regarding the installation and use of surveillance cameras.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] The law is not applicable for the exchange of personal data between government agencies.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] Complaints about privacy infringement is a lengthy process.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] In New Zealand, the Privacy Act 1993 (replaced by Privacy Act 2020) sets out principles in relation to the collection, use, disclosure, security and access to personal information.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] The introduction into the New Zealand common law of a tort covering invasion of personal privacy at least by public disclosure of private facts was at issue in *Hosking v Runting* and was accepted by the Court of Appeal.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p02] In *Rogers v TVNZ Ltd*, the Supreme Court indicated it had some misgivings with how the tort was introduced, but chose not to interfere with it at that stage.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p03] Federal Republic of Nigeria's constitution offers its constituents the right to privacy as well as privacy protection.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p03] The following can be found in the constitution pertaining to this: "The privacy of citizens, their homes, correspondence, telephone conversations and telegraphic communications is hereby guaranteed and protected".
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p03] Additionally, as a member of the United Nations, Nigeria is bound by the universal declaration of Human Rights which states in article twelve "No one shall be subjected to arbitrary interference with his privacy, family, home or correspondence, nor to attacks upon his honor and reputation.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p03] Nigeria is one of the few African countries that is building on the privacy laws.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p03] This is evident in the fact that Nine years later in the year 2008, the Cybersecurity and Information Protection Agency Bill was passed.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p03] This bill is responsible for the creation of the Cybersecurity and Information Protection Agency.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p03] This agency is tasked with the job of preventing cyberattacks and regulating the Nigerian information technology industry.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p03] Additional laws have been passed that are meant to prevent the disclosure of information without permission and the intercepting of some form of transaction with or without evil intent.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p03] In Article III, Section 3, paragraph 1 of the 1987 Constitution of the Philippines lets its audience know that "The privacy of communication and correspondence shall be inviolable except upon lawful order of the court, or when public safety or order requires otherwise as prescribed by law".
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p03] Not only does this country grant the Filipinos the right to privacy, but it also protects its people's right to privacy by attaching consequences to the violation of it thereof.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p03] In the year 2012, the Philippines passed the Republic Act No.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p03] 10173, also known as the "Data Privacy Act of 2012".
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p03] This act extended privacy regulations and laws to apply to more than just individual industries.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p03] This act also offered protection of data belonging to the people regardless of where it is stored, be it in private spheres or not.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p03] In that very same year, the cybercrime prevention law was passed.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p03] This law was "intended to protect and safeguard the integrity of computer and communications systems" and prevent them from being misused.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p03] Not only does the Philippines have these laws, but it has also set aside agents that are tasked with regulating these privacy rules and due ensure the punishment of the violators.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p03] Additionally, with the constitution, previous laws that have been passed but that are in violation of the laws above have been said to be void and nullified.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p03] Another way this country has shown their dedication in executing this law is extending it to the government sphere as well.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p03] Additionally, as a member of the United Nations, the Philippines is bound by the Universal Declaration of Human Rights which states in article two "No one shall be subjected to arbitrary interference with his privacy, family, home or correspondence, nor to attacks upon his honor and reputation.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p03] The Law of the Russian Federation "On Personal Data" as of 27 July 2006 No.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p03] 152-FZ, regulating the processing of personal data by means of automation equipment.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p03] It is the operator who is required to comply with that Act.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p03] As a general rule, consent of the individual is required for processing, i.e. obtaining, organizing, accumulating, holding, adjusting (updating, modifying), using, disclosing (including transfer), impersonating, blocking or destroying of his personal data.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p03] This rule doesn't apply where such processing is necessary for performance of the contract, to which an individual is a party.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p03] The Kingdom of Saudi Arabia enacted the Personal Data Protection Law (PDPL) by Royal Decree No.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p03] M/19 dated 9/2/1443 AH (16 September 2021), with amendments by Royal Decree No.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p03] The law entered into force on 14 September 2023 and full compliance was required by 14 September 2024 after a one-year grace period.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p03] The PDPL is the first comprehensive data protection law in Saudi Arabia and is enforced by the Saudi Authority for Data and Artificial Intelligence (SDAIA) until the National Data Management Office (NDMO) assumes long-term oversight.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p03] The law applies to the processing of personal data of individuals residing in Saudi Arabia by any controller or processor inside or outside the Kingdom, giving it broader extraterritorial reach than the European Union's General Data Protection Regulation.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p03] Violations are punishable by administrative fines of up to 5 million Saudi riyals (approximately US$1.33 million), doubled for repeat offenses.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p03] Disclosure of sensitive personal data with intent to harm is punishable by imprisonment of up to two years and fines of up to 3 million Saudi riyals.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p03] Singapore, like other Commonwealth jurisdictions, relies primarily on common law, and the law of confidence is employed for privacy protection cases.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p03] For example, privacy can be protected indirectly through various common law torts: defamation, trespass, nuisance, negligence, and breach of confidence.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p03] In February 2002, however, the Singaporean government decided that the common law approach was inadequate for their emerging globalized technological economy.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p03] Thus, the National Internet Advisory Committee published the Model Data Protection Code for the Private Sector, which set standards for personal data protection and was influenced by the EU Data Protection Directive and the OECD Guidelines on the Protection of Privacy.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p03] In the private sector, businesses can still choose to adopt the Model Code, but in 2005 Parliament decided that Singapore needed a more comprehensive legislative privacy framework.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p03] In January 2013, Singapore's Personal Data Protection Act 2012 came into effect in three separate but related phases.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p03] The phases continued through July 2014 and dealt with the creation of the Personal Data Protection Commission, the national Do Not Call Registry, and general data protection Rules.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p03] The Act's general purpose "is to govern the collection, use and disclosure of personal data by organisations" while acknowledging the individual's right to control their personal data and the organizations' legal needs to collect this data.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p03] It imposes eight obligations on those organizations that use personal data: consent, purpose limitation, notification, access, correction, accuracy, protection/security, and retention.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p03] The Act prohibits transfer of personal data to countries with privacy protection standards that are lower than those outlined in the general data protection rules.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p03] The Personal Data Protection Commission is responsible for enforcing the Act, which is based primarily on a complaints-based system.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p03] The punishments for violating the Act can include being ordered by the commission to stop collecting and using personal data, to destroy the data, or to pay a penalty of up to $1 million.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p03] The Constitution of South Africa guarantees the most general right to privacy for all its citizens.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p03] This provides the main protection for personal data privacy so far.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p03] The Protection of Personal Information Act 2013 (POPI) was signed into act, focusing on data privacy and is inspired by other foreign national treaties like the European Union.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p03] The recording of conversations over phone and internet is not allowed without the permission of both parties with the Regulation of Interception of Communications and Provision of Communications Related Act (2002).
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p03] In addition, South Africa is part of the Southern African Development Community and the African Union.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p03] 9 of 2022, effective since 19 March 2022, applies to processing within Sri Lanka and extends extraterritorially to controllers or processors offering goods and services to individuals in Sri Lanka and/or monitoring their behavior in the country.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p03] The Data Act is the world's first national data protection law and was enacted in Sweden on 11 May 1973.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p03] The law was then superseded on 24 October 1998 by the Personal Data Act (Sw.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p03] *Personuppgiftslagen*) that implemented the 1995 EU Data Protection Directive.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p03] The main legislation over personal data privacy for the personal and private sector in Switzerland is the Swiss Federal Protection Act, specifically the Data Protection Act, a specific section under the Swiss Federal Protection Act.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p03] The Data Protection Act has been enacted since 1992 and is in charge of measuring the consent of sharing of personal data, along with other legislation like the Telecommunication Act and the Unfair Competition Act.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p03] The Act generally guides on how to collect, process, store, data, use, disclose, and destruct data.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p03] The Data Inspection Board is in charge of overseeing data breaches and privacy enforcement.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p03] Personal data must be protected against illegal use by "being processed in good faith and must be proportionate".
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p03] Also, the reason for the transfer of personal data must be known by the time of data transfer.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p03] Data not associated with people (not personal data) is not protected by the Data Protection Act.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p03] Switzerland is a white-listed country, meaning that it is a nation that has proper levels of data protection under the surveillance by the European Commission (EU Commission).
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p03] Switzerland is not under the EU Data Protection Directive 95/46 EC.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p03] However, the data protection regulations are sufficient to meet European Union (EU) regulations without being a member of the EU.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p03] In addition, Switzerland is part of the Council of Europe and the Organisation for Economic Cooperation and Development.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p03] The Data Inspection Board of Switzerland is a member of the International Conference of Data Protection and Privacy Commissioners, European Data Protection Authorities, the EU Article 29 Working Party, and the Nordic Data Protection Authorities.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p03] The right to privacy is not explicitly mentioned in the Republic of China Constitution, but it can be protected indirectly through judicial interpretation.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p03] The Justices first made reference to privacy being a protected right in the 1992 "Interpretation of Council of Grand Justices No.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p03] 293 on Disputes Concerning Debtors' Rights," but it was not directly or explicitly declared to be a right.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p03] In 1995, Taiwan passed the Computer-Processed Personal Data Protection Act which was influenced by the OECD Guidelines and enforced by each separate Ministry depending on their industry sector responsibility.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p03] It only protected personal information managed by government agencies and certain industries.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p03] In 2010, Taiwan enacted the Personal Data Protection Act that laid out more comprehensive guidelines for the public and private sectors and was still enforced by individual Ministries.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p03] In the 2010 Act, personal data is protected and defined as any "data which is sufficient to, directly or indirectly, identify that person", and includes data such as name, date of birth, fingerprints, occupation, medical records, and financial status, among many others.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p03] Additionally, chapter 28 of the Criminal Code outlines punishments for privacy violations in article 315, sections 315-1 and 315–2.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p03] The sections primarily address issues of search and seizure and criminal punishment for wrongful invasion of privacy.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p03] Finally, articles 18(I),184(I), and 195(I) of the Taiwanese Civil Code address the "personality right" to privacy and the right to compensation when one injures the "rights" of another, such as when someone uses another's name illegally.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p03] Thailand's unique history of being an authoritarian buffer state during the Cold War and being under the constant threat of a coup d'état means that privacy laws have so far been limited in order to preserve national security and public safety.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p03] Thailand uses bureaucratic surveillance to maintain national security and public safety, which explains the 1991 Civil Registration Act that was passed to protect personal data in computerized record-keeping and data-processing done by the government.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p03] The legislature passed the Official Information Act 1997 to provide basic data protection by limiting personal data collection and retention in the public sector.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p03] It defines personal information in a national context in relation to state agencies.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p03] Two communication technology related laws, the Electronic Transactions Act 2001 and the Computer Crime Act 2007, provide some data privacy protection and enforcement mechanisms.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p03] Nevertheless, Thailand still lacks legislation that explicitly addresses privacy security.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p03] Thus, with the need for a more general and all-encompassing data protection law, the legislature proposed the Personal Data Protection Bill in 2013, which is heavily influenced by the OECD Guidelines and the EU Directive.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p03] The draft law is still under evaluation and its enactment date is not yet finalized.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p03] Privacy and data protection in Ukraine is mainly regulated by the Law of Ukraine No.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p03] 2297-VI 'On Personal Data Protection' enacted on 1 June 2010.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p03] On 20 December 2012 legislation was substantially amended.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p03] However, there is no independent tort law doctrine which recognises a right to privacy.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p03] This has been confirmed on a number of occasions.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p03] Processing of personal information is regulated by the Data Protection Act 2018, supplementing the EU General Data Protection Regulation, which is still in force (in amended form) after the UK's exit from the EU as "retained EU legislation".
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p03] The Data Protection Act of 2018 is the United Kingdom's main legislation protecting personal data and how it should be collected, processed, stored and shared.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p03] The goal of the Privacy and Electronic Communications Regulations is to protect individuals’ privacy and control over their electronic communications while promoting responsible and transparent practices by organizations that engage in electronic marketing and in the use of tracking technologies.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p03] The United Kingdom General Data Protection Regulation, is the domestic version of the European Union's General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR), implemented into UK law through the Data Protection Act 2018 and came into effect alongside the EU GDPR in May 2018.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p03] UK GDPR governs data protection and privacy within the UK applying to the processing of personal data by organizations operating within the UK.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p03] It includes specific provisions tailored to the UK's legal framework and requirements.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p03] The UK GDPR aims to ensure that personal data is processed legally, fairly and with full transparency while individuals are given control over the handling of their personal data.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p03] For detailed guidance and the latest updates on compliance with United Kingdom privacy laws, businesses and individuals can refer to resources provided by the https://ico.org.uk/ and stay informed about developments in UK privacy law through expert analyses and updates.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p03] Constitution does not explicitly define a right to privacy.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p03] In 1890, Louis Brandeis (later a Supreme Court justice) and another lawyer, Samuel D.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p03] Warren II, published an influential article called "The Right to Privacy" in the *Harvard Law Review* arguing that the United States Constitution and common law allowed for the deduction of a general "right to privacy".
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p03] To help rule on various privacy-related questions, court cases have applied the Fourth Amendment right to be free of unwarranted search or seizure, the First Amendment right to free assembly, and the Fourteenth Amendment due process right.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p03] A tort expert and Dean of the College of Law at University of California, Berkeley, William Lloyd Prosser argued in 1960 that "privacy" was composed of four separate torts, the only unifying element of which was a (vague) "right to be left alone".
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p03] Appropriating the plaintiff's identity for the defendant's benefit (see Personality rights § United States).
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p03] Appropriation of one's likeness is considered the oldest of the main American privacy torts.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p03] It involves the right to control where one's appearance and other aspects of their "likeness," such as their voice and name, appear in areas like advertising and other media.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p03] As noted by the California Jury, successful cases built on the appropriation of a person's likeness must typically involve them being harmed in some way by this usage, which was non-consensual and contributed to some benefit, often financial, to the person or company using their image.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p03] Placing the plaintiff in a false light in the public eye.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p03] Breach of confidence: publicly disclosing private facts about the plaintiff.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p03] Public Disclosure of Private Facts or Publicity Given to Private Life is a tort under privacy law that protects individuals from the unauthorized dissemination of private information that is not of public concern.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p03] This tort aims to safeguard an individual's right to privacy and prevent unwarranted intrusion into their personal lives.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p03] The Privacy Act of 1974 is foundational, establishing a code of fair information practices that govern the collection, maintenance, use, and dissemination of information about individuals that is maintained in systems of records by federal agencies.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p03] This act allows individuals to review and amend their records, ensuring personal information is handled transparently and responsibly by the government.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p03] Enacted in 1996, the Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act (HIPAA) protects sensitive patient health information from being disclosed without the patient's consent or knowledge.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p03] HIPAA sets the standard for protecting sensitive patient data held by health care providers, insurance companies, and their business associates.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p03] The Federal Trade Commission plays a crucial role in enforcing federal privacy laws that protect consumer privacy and security, particularly in commercial practices.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p03] It oversees the enforcement of laws such as the Fair Credit Reporting Act, which regulates the collection and use of consumer credit information.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p03] One of the central privacy policies concerning minors is the Children's Online Privacy Protection Act (COPPA), which requires children under the age of thirteen to gain parental consent before putting any personal information online.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p03] Individual states also enact their own privacy laws.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p03] The California Consumer Privacy Act is one of the most stringent privacy laws in the U.S.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p03] It provides California residents with the right to know about the personal data collected about them, the right to delete personal information held by businesses, and the right to opt-out of the sale of their personal information.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p03] Businesses must disclose their data collection and sharing practices to consumers and allow consumers to access their data and opt-out if they choose.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p03] The Act recently expanded existing consumer rights in the state in 2023, providing citizens the right to reduce the collection of data and correct false information.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p03] Enforcement of these laws is specific to the statutes and the authorities responsible.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p03] For instance, HIPAA violations can lead to substantial fines imposed by the Department of Health and Human Services, while the Federal Trade Commission handles penalties under consumer protection laws.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p03] State laws are enforced by respective state attorneys general or designated state agencies.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p03] A handful of lists and databases help risk managers research U.S. state and federal laws that define liability.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p03] The Perkins Coie Security Breach Notification Chart is a set of articles (one per state) that define data breach notification requirements among U.S. states.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p03] The NCSL Security Breach Notification Laws is a list of U.S. state statutes that define data breach notification requirements.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p03] Though the right to privacy exists in several regulations, the most effective privacy protections come in the form of constitutional articles of Uzbekistan.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p03] Varying aspects of the right to privacy are protected in different ways by different situations.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p03] Vietnam, lacking a general data protection law, relies on Civil Code regulations relating to personal data protection.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p03] The legislation, however, does not define what qualifies as proper.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p03] In 2015, the Vietnam legislature introduced the Law on Information Security, which ensures better information safety and protection online and in user's computer software.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p03] It took effect on 1 July 2016 and is Vietnam's first overarching data protection legislation.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p03] Privacy laws focus on protecting individuals' rights to control their personal and sensitive information, while preventing unauthorized intrusion into their private lives.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p03] They encompass strict regulations governing data protection, confidentiality, surveillance, and the use of personal information by both government and corporate entities.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p03] Trespass to land laws focus on breaches of privacy rights related to physical intrusion onto an individual's property or personal domain without consent.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p03] This involves illegal activities such as: entering an individual's residence without consent, conducting surveillance using physical methods (e.g., deploying hidden cameras), or any unauthorized entry onto the individual's property.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p03] Negligence laws generally address situations where individuals or entities fail to exercise appropriate caution in protecting the privacy rights of others, often holding them accountable through severe penalties like heavy fines.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p03] This aims to ensure compliance and deter future violations, involving incidents such as any mishandling of sensitive data, poor security measures leading to data breaches, or any non-compliance with privacy policies and regulations.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p03] Fiduciary laws regulate the relationships characterized by trust and confidence, where the fiduciary accepts and complies with the legal responsibility for duties of care, loyalty, good faith, confidentiality, and more when entrusted in serving the best interests of a beneficiary.
[src:ccpa-privacy/privacy-law-p03] In terms of privacy, fiduciary obligations may extend to professionals like lawyers, doctors, financial advisors, and others responsible for handling confidential information, as a result of a duty of confidentiality to their clients or patients.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] The **right to be forgotten** (**RTBF**) is the right to have private information about a person removed from Internet searches and other directories in some circumstances.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] The issue arose from the desires of individuals to "determine the development of their life in an autonomous way, without being perpetually or periodically stigmatized as a consequence of a specific action performed in the past".
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] The right entitles a person to have data about them deleted so that it can no longer be discovered by third parties, particularly through search engines.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] Those who favor a right to be forgotten cite its necessity due to issues such as revenge porn sites and references to past petty crimes appearing in search engine listings for a person's name.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] The main concern is for the potentially undue influence that such results may exert upon a person's online reputation indefinitely if not removed.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] Those who oppose the right worry about its effect on the right to freedom of expression and whether creating a right to be forgotten would result in a decreased quality of the Internet, censorship, and the rewriting of history.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] The right to be forgotten is distinct from the right to privacy.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] The right to privacy constitutes information that is not known publicly, whereas the right to be forgotten involves revoking public access to information that was known publicly at a certain time.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] Argentina has had lawsuits by celebrities against Google and Yahoo! in which the plaintiffs demand the removal of certain search results, and require removal of links to photographs.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] One case, brought by artist Virginia da Cunha, involved photographs which had originally been taken with her permission and uploaded with her permission, however she alleged that the search results improperly associated her photographs with pornography.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] Da Cunha's case achieved initial success resulting in Argentina search engines not showing images of the particular celebrity, however, this decision is on appeal.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] Virginia Simari, the judge in favor of Da Cunha, stated that people have the right to control their image and avert others from "capturing, reproducing, broadcasting, or publishing one's image without permission".
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] Argentina's efforts to protect their people's right to be forgotten has been called "the most complete" because individuals are able to correct, delete, or update information about themselves: overall, their information is bound to remain confidential.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] In 2016, a Chinese court in Beijing rejected an argument for the right to be forgotten when a judge ruled in favor of Baidu in a lawsuit over removing search results.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] It was the first of such cases to be heard in Chinese court.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] In the suit, Ren Jiayu sued Chinese search engine Baidu over search results that negatively associated him with a previous employer, Wuxi Taoshi Biotechnology.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] Ren argued that by posting the search results, Baidu had infringed upon his right of name and right of reputation, both protected under Chinese law.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] Because of these protections, Ren believed he had a right to be forgotten by removing these search results.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] The court ruled against Ren, claiming his name is a collection of common characters and as a result the search results were derived from relevant words.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] The court described search results as neutral findings based on an algorithm and stated that retaining such information was necessary for the public.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] As the call for personal information protection has grown louder, China has taken active measures to strengthen data protection.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] In 2018, China released the national standard "Information Security Technology—Personal Information Security Specification," which was the first systematic regulation for personal information protection.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] In 2020, the updated national standards replaced the version that came into effect in 2018.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] Subsequently, in 2021, China introduced the formal legal framework, the "Personal Information Protection Law of the People's Republic of China" (PIPL).
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] The enactment of this law filled a legal gap and made detailed provisions regarding the collection, storage, use, transfer, and deletion of personal information.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] For businesses, it is essential to follow the principles of legality, fairness, and necessity when collecting and using personal data, ensuring transparency and data security.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] Moreover, the PIPL strengthens the regulation of cross-border data flows, requiring risk assessments in specific cases and mandating additional protective measures for users.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] Europe's data protection laws do not implement a "right to be forgotten", but a more limited "right to [data] erasure".
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] Although the term "right to be forgotten" is a relatively new idea, the European Court of Justice legally solidified that the "right to be forgotten" is a human right when they ruled against Google in the *Costeja* case on May 13, 2014.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] This raises questions about the limitations of application in a jurisdiction include the inability to require removal of information possessed by companies outside the jurisdiction.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] There is no global framework to allow individuals control over their online image.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] In 1995, the European Union adopted the European Data Protection Directive (Directive 95/46/EC) to regulate the processing of personal data.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] Data protection is now considered a component of human rights law.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] The European General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR), in force since 2018, provides protection and exemption for companies listed as "media" companies, like newspapers and other journalistic work.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] However, Google purposely opted out of being classified as a "media" company, therefore the company is not protected.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] Judges in the European Union ruled that because the international corporation, Google, is a collector and processor of data it should be classified as a "data controller" under the meaning of the EU data protection directive.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] These "data controllers" are required under EU law to remove data that is "inadequate, irrelevant, or no longer relevant", making this directive of global importance.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] In Article 12 of the Directive 95/46/EC the EU gave a legal basis to Internet protection for individuals.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] A *right to be forgotten* was replaced by a more limited *right of erasure* in Article 17 of the GDPR, which came into force in May 2018.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] To exercise the right to be forgotten and request removal from a search engine, one must complete a form through the search engine's website.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] Google's removal request process requires the applicant to identify their country of residence, personal information, a list of the URLs to be removed along with a short description, and – in some cases – attachment of legal identification.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] The applicant receives an email from Google confirming the request but the request must be assessed before it is approved for removal.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] If the request is approved, searches using the individual's name will no longer result in the content appearing in search results.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] The content remains online and is not erased.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] After a request is filled, their removals team reviews the request, weighing "the individual's right to privacy against the public's right to know", deciding if the website is "inadequate, irrelevant or no longer relevant, or excessive in relation to the purposes for which they were processed".
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] Google has formed an Advisory Council of various professors, lawyers, and government officials from around Europe to provide guidelines for these decisions.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] However, the review process is still a mystery to the general public.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] Guidelines set by EU regulators were not released until November 2014, but Google began to take action on this much sooner than that, which (according to one author) allowed them "to shape interpretation to [their] own ends".
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] In May 2015, eighty academics called for more transparency from Google in an open letter.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] The form asks people to select one of the 27 countries that make up the European Union, as well as Andorra, Iceland, Liechtenstein, Monaco, Norway, San Marino, Switzerland, and the United Kingdom, plus several dependent territories.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] "The form allows an individual or someone representing an individual to put in a request" for the removal of any URLs believed to be a violation of the individual's privacy.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] Regardless of who is submitting the form, some form of photo identification of the person the form is being submitted for must be present.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] This is meant to serve as proof that the person for whom the request was made for does in fact approve.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] If Google refuses a request to delink material, Europeans can appeal to their local data protection agency.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] As of May 2015, the British Information Commissioner's Office (ICO) had treated 184 such complaints, and overturned Google's decision in about a quarter of those.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] If Google fails to comply with a decision of the ICO, it can face legal action.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] Google indeed acknowledged that some of its search result removals, affecting articles that were of public interest, were incorrect, and reinstated the links a week later.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] Google notifies websites that have URLs delinked, and various news organizations, such as BBC, have published lists of delinked articles.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] Complainants have been named in news commentary regarding those delinkings.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] In August 2015 the ICO issued an enforcement action requiring Google to delink some of these more recent articles from searches for a complainant's name, after Google refused to do so.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] Some academics have criticized news organizations and Google for their behavior.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] In July 2015, Google accidentally revealed data on delinkings that "shows 95% of Google privacy requests are from citizens out to protect personal and private information – not criminals, politicians and public figures." Only 5% of requests were made by criminals, politicians, and public figures.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] One request for data removal was from a British doctor requesting to have 50 links removed on past botched medical procedures.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] Google agreed to remove three search results containing his personal information.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] The European Union has been advocating for the delinkings requested by EU citizens to be implemented by Google not just in European versions of Google (as in google.co.uk, google.fr, etc.), but on google.com and other international subdomains.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] Regulators want delinkings to be implemented so that the law cannot be circumvented in any way.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] Google has refused the French Data Protection Agency's demand to apply the right internationally.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] Due in part to their refusal to comply with the recommendation of the privacy regulating board Google has become the subject of a four-year-long antitrust investigation by the European Commission.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] In September 2015, the French Data Protection Agency dismissed Google's appeal.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] The French Data Protection Agency appealed to the EU courts to seek action on Google for failing to delink in its global servers.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] As of September 2015, the most delinked site is *www.facebook.com*.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] Three of Google's own sites, *groups.google.com*, *plus.google.com* and *www.youtube.com* are among the ten most delinked sites.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] In addition to Google, Yahoo! and Bing have also made forms available for making delinking requests.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] In September 2019, the European Court of Justice ruled that the right to be forgotten did not apply outside of its member states.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] The ruling meant that Google did not have to delete the names of individuals from all of its international versions.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] They do not however need to obtain explicit consent before indexing such data, even though the law typically requires explicit consent before data processing, on the basis that such examination would not be within the powers, responsibiities or capabilities of a search engine.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] The consequences of this judgment have been criticised in data protection scholarship, as its logic implies that technologies that are designed in a way that renders data protection compliance impossible may be given the right to avoid the law.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] In December 2022, the judges in Luxembourg further extended the right to be forgotten in the case C-460/20 *TU, RE v Google LLC*.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] The case related to two managers of a group of investment companies, who argued that three unflattering news articles should be 'de-referenced' from the search engine results of Google, when searching for their names.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] They claimed that the information presented in the articles was wrong factually, which raised the question whether search engine operators need to check the accuracy of the information.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] Additionally, the applicants required that photographs showing them in preview images – or thumbnails – when carrying out a search ought to be removed.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] In this judgment the European Court of Justice largely agreed with the request of the applicants.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] Search engine operators such as Google are required to de-reference the respective information, if a person who seeks de-referencing submits 'relevant and sufficient' evidence capable of substantiating his or her request, and thereby manifests the inaccuracy of the information found (para.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] For thumbnails an independent assessment must be performed, but essentially the same thinking applies.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] Europe's jurisdiction of data also extends beyond its borders into countries that does not have "adequate" protections.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] For instance, Europe's transfer of data to vulnerable countries are limited, resulting in companies like Google and Amazon establishing European data centers to quarantine data from Europe.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] He initially attempted to have the article removed by complaining to the Spanish Data Protection Agency, which rejected the claim on the grounds that it was lawful and accurate, but accepted a complaint against Google and asked Google to remove the results.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] Google sued in the Spanish *Audiencia Nacional* (National High Court) which referred a series of questions to the European Court of Justice.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] The court ruled that search engines are responsible for the content they point to and thus, Google was required to comply with EU data privacy laws.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] On its first day of compliance only (May 30, 2014), Google received 12,000 requests to have personal details removed from its search engine.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] Stopp, attorney for Werlé and Lauber, had won a default judgment in German court, on behalf of Lauber, against the Wikimedia Foundation.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] According to the Electronic Frontier Foundation, Werlé's lawyers also challenged an Internet service provider in Austria which published the names of the convicted killers.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] Wikimedia is based in the United States, where the First Amendment protects freedom of speech and freedom of the press.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] In Germany, the law seeks to protect the name and likenesses of private persons from unwanted publicity.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] On January 18, 2008, a court in Hamburg supported the personality rights of Werlé, which by German law includes removing his name from archive coverage of the case.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] On November 12, 2009, *The New York Times* reported that Wolfgang Werlé had a case pending against the Wikimedia Foundation in a German court.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] The editors of the German-language Wikipedia article about Sedlmayr removed the names of the murderers, which have since then been restored to the article.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] *The Guardian* observed that the lawsuit has resulted in the Streisand effect, an upsurge in publicity for the case resulting from the legal action.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] On December 15, 2009, the German Federal Court of Justice (*Bundesgerichtshof*) in Karlsruhe ruled that German websites do not have to check their archives in order to provide permanent protection of personality rights for convicted criminals.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] The case occurred after the names of the brothers were found on the website of *Deutschlandradio*, in an archive article dating from July 2000.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] The presiding judge Gregor Galke stated "This is not a blank check", and stated that the right to rehabilitation of offenders had been taken into consideration.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] On November 28, 2019, the federal constitutional court in Karlsruhe ruled that German murderer Paul Termann had the right to be forgotten.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] The 2012 draft European Data Protection Regulation Article 17 detailed the "right to be forgotten and to erasure".
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] The EU defines "data controllers" as "people or bodies that collect and manage personal data".
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] Where the controller has authorized a third party publication of personal data, the controller shall be considered responsible for that publication".
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] In the situation that a data controller does not take all reasonable steps then they will be fined heavily.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] The European Parliament was once "expected to adopt the proposals in first reading in the April 2013 Plenary session".
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] The right to be forgotten was replaced by a more limited right to erasure in the version of the GDPR adopted by the European Parliament in March 2014.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] The European Union is an influential group of states, and this tendency towards the right to be forgotten in the EU is an indicator of its recognition globally as a right.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] To support this, in 2012 the Obama Administration released a "Privacy Bill of Rights" to protect consumers online.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] In June 2014, Privacy Commissioner Allan Chiang Yam-wang (蔣任宏) expressed his support for introducing the right to be forgotten to Hong Kong.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] Opposition expressed their worry that the right would inhibit freedom of information, and introducing erase from history.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] Charles Mok, Hong Kong Legislative Councillor from I.T. occupation, oppose to introduce the right to be forgotten, citing the difficulty of enforcing and abuses of practising the right.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] He described the abuses as "right to be deleteion" In July 2015, Stephen Wong Kai-yi (黃繼兒) replaced Chiang's position and promised not to introduce the right to be forgotten.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] In April 2016, the Delhi High Court began to examine the issue after a Delhi banker requested to have his personal details removed from search results after a marital dispute.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] In this case, due to the dispute being settled, the banker's request is valid.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] The High Court has asked for a reply from Google and other search engine companies by September 19, upon which the court will continue to investigate the issue.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] In January 2017, the Karnataka High Court upheld the right to be forgotten, in a case involving a woman who originally went to court in order to get a marriage certificate annulled, claiming to have never been married to the man on the certificate.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] After the two parties came to an agreement, the woman's father wanted her name to be removed from search engines regarding criminal cases in the high court.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] The Karnataka High Court approved the father's request, stating that she had a right to be forgotten.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] As of February 2017, the Delhi High Court is hearing a case involving a man requesting to have information regarding his mother and wife to be removed from a search engine.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] The man believes that having his name linked to the search is hindering his employment options.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] The Delhi High Court is still working on the case, along with the issue of whether or not a right to be forgotten should be a legal standard in India.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] Currently, there is no legal standard for the right to be forgotten, but if implemented, this would mean that citizens no longer need to file a case in order to request for information from search engines to be removed.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] This case could have significant impacts on the right to be forgotten and search engines in India.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] In May 2016, South Korea's Communications Commission (KCC) announced citizens will be able to request search engines and website administrators to restrict their own postings from being accessible publicly.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] The KCC released "Guidelines on the Right to Request Access Restrictions on Personal Internet Postings", which took effect in June 2016 and do not apply to third party contents.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] To the extent that the right to be forgotten concerns a data subject's right to limit the searchability of third party postings about him/her, the Guideline does not constitute a right to be forgotten.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] The guidelines created by the KCC include that data subjects can remove content that includes the URL links, and any evidence consisting of personal information.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] The commission included different amendments to the guideline.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] This includes describing the Guidelines as a "minimum" and "preliminary" precaution regarding privacy rights in vague areas of existing laws.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] The guideline encompasses foreign Internet companies that provide translation services for South Korean consumers.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] In order to have a person's information "forgotten" he or she has to go through a three step process: the issue posted with the URL, proof of ownership of the post, grounds for the request.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] When posting the URL, the web operator has the right to preserve the posting issue.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] The second being that if the post is relevant to public interest, web operators will process this request on the terms of relevance.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] The right to be forgotten was added in the constitution of the Canton of Geneva in the new article 21A *right to digital integrity* voted on June 18, 2023.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] Consideration of the right to be forgotten occurred in US case law, specifically in *Melvin v.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] Reid* (1931), an ex-prostitute was charged with murder and then acquitted; she subsequently tried to assume a quiet and anonymous place in society.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] However, the 1925 movie *The Red Kimono* revealed her history, and she successfully sued the producer.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] FR Publishing Corp.* (1940), the plaintiff, William James Sidis, was a former child prodigy who wished to spend his adult life quietly, without recognition; however, this was disrupted by an article in *The New Yorker*.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] The court held here that there were limits to the right to control one's life and facts about oneself, and held that there is social value in published facts, and that a person cannot ignore their celebrity status merely because they want to.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] These criticisms are consistent with the proposal that the only information that can be removed by user's request is content that they themselves uploaded.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] In a June 2014 opinion piece in *Forbes*, columnist Joseph Steinberg noted that "many privacy protections that Americans believe that they enjoy – even some guaranteed by law – have, in fact, been eroded or even obliterated by technological advances".
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] On March 11, 2015, Intelligence Squared US, an organization that stages Oxford-Style debates, held an event concerning the question, "Should the U.S. adopt the 'Right to be Forgotten' online?" The side against the motion won with a 56% majority of the voting audience.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] While opinions among experts are divided in the U.S., one survey indicated that 9 in 10 Americans want some form of the right to be forgotten.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] The consumer rights organization Consumer Watchdog has filed a complaint with the Federal Trade Commission for Americans to obtain the right as well.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] In June 2018, California enacted the California Consumer Privacy Act, providing consumers with the right to delete their personal information from covered businesses.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] In October 2023, the state enacted the California Delete Act, requiring the California Privacy Protection Agency to establish a one-stop shop deletion mechanism for consumers to direct data brokers to delete their personal information.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] In January 2021, the *Boston Globe* announced a program to allow subjects of relatively inconsequential stories to have the stories contextualized, removed from Google searches or anonymized.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] In January 2025, it was reported that *The Oregonian, The Plain Dealer, Bangor Daily News, The Atlanta Journal-Constitution* and NJ.com offered similar services.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] The regulatory differences in the protection of personal data between countries has real impact on international relations.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] The right to be forgotten, specifically, is a matter of EU-US relations when applied to cross-border data flow, as it raises questions about territorial sovereignty.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] The structure of the Westphalian international system assumes that the reach of a country's jurisdiction is limited to its geographic territory.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] However, online interactions are independent of geographic location and present across multiple locations, rendering the traditional concept of territorial sovereignty moot.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] Therefore, the EU and the United States are forced to confront their regulatory differences and negotiate on a set of regulations that apply to all foreign companies processing and handling data of European citizens and residents.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] The regulatory differences on the right to be forgotten along with numerous other data protection rights have affected discussions and negotiations on trans-Atlantic data privacy regulations.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] A case in point is the EU and the United States' endeavors to develop the International Safe Harbor Privacy Principles agreement, a data transfer pact that enables the transfer of data between the EU and US companies in a manner consistent with the EU's data protection schemes.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] Article 25 of the Data Protection Directive articulates that cross-border transfer of data can take place only if the "third country in question ensures an adequate level of protection," meaning that the country meets the EU's minimum standards of data protection.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] The standards include, among many provisions, a component that protects the right to "opt out" of further processing or transmission of personal data, with the assumption that data may not be further processed in ways inconsistent with the intent for which they were collected.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] Given the inconsistencies between the EU and the United States on numerous digital privacy regulations, including the right to be forgotten, Article 25 poses a threat to trans-Atlantic data flows.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] As a result of the mass surveillance performed by the US government on European citizens' data, the Safe Harbor agreement has been invalidated by the European Union Court of Justice in its *Schrems* case.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] The Safe Harbor agreement has now been replaced by the Privacy Shield principles.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] Businesses that manage their clients' online reputations have responded to the European Court ruling by exercising the right to be forgotten as a means to remove unfavorable information.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] One technique used by reputation consulting companies is to submit multiple requests for each link, written with different angles in an attempt to get links removed.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] Google, for example, does not limit the number of requests that can be submitted on the removal of a given link.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] Major criticisms stem from the idea that the right to be forgotten would restrict the right to freedom of speech.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] Many nations, and the United States in particular (with the First Amendment to the United States Constitution), have very strong domestic freedom of speech laws, which would be challenging to reconcile with the right to be forgotten.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] Some academics see that only a limited form of the right to be forgotten would be reconcilable with US constitutional law; the right of an individual to delete data that they have personally submitted.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] In this limited form of the right individuals could not have material removed that has been uploaded by others, as demanding the removal of information could constitute censorship and a reduction in the freedom of expression in many countries.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] Sandra Coliver of the Open Society Justice Initiative argues that not all rights must be compatible and this conflict between the two rights is not detrimental to the survival of either.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] The draft General Data Protection Regulation was written broadly and this has caused concern.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] It has attracted criticism that its enactment would require data controlling companies to go to great lengths to identify third parties with the information and remove it.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] In addition to this, there are concerns about the requirement to take down information that others have posted about an individual; the definition of personal data in Article 4(2) includes "any information relating to" the individual.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] This, critics have claimed, would require companies to take down any information relating to an individual, regardless of its source, which would amount to censorship, and result in the big data companies eradicating much data to comply with this.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] Such removal can impact the accuracy and ability of businesses and individuals to perform business intelligence, particularly due diligence to comply with anti bribery, anticorruption, and know your customer laws.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] Other criticism revolves around the principle of accountability.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] There were concerns that the proposed General Data Protection Regulation would result in Google and other Internet search engines not producing neutral search results, but rather producing biased and patchy results, and compromising the integrity of Internet-based information.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] Despite these criticisms and Google's action, the company's CEO, Larry Page worries that the ruling will be "used by other governments that aren't as forward and progressive as Europe to do bad things", though has since distanced himself from that statement.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] For example, pianist Dejan Lazic cited the "Right To Be Forgotten" in trying to remove a negative review about his performance from *The Washington Post*.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] He claimed that the critique was "defamatory, mean-spirited, opinionated, offensive and simply irrelevant for the arts". and the St.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] Lawrence parish of the Roman Catholic church in Kutno, Poland asked Google to remove the Polish Wikipedia page about it, (in Polish) without any allegations mentioned therein as of that date.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] Index on Censorship claimed that the *Costeja* ruling "allows individuals to complain to search engines about information they do not like with no legal oversight.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] This is akin to marching into a library and forcing it to pulp books.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] Although the ruling is intended for private individuals it opens the door to anyone who wants to whitewash their personal history… The Court's decision is a retrograde move that misunderstands the role and responsibility of search engines and the wider Internet.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] In 2014, the Gerry Hutch page on the English Wikipedia was among the first Wikipedia pages to be removed by several search engines' query results in the European Union.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] *The Daily Telegraph* said, on 6 August 2014, that Wikipedia co-founder Jimmy Wales "described the EU's Right to be Forgotten as deeply immoral, as the organisation that operates the online encyclopedia warned the ruling will result in an Internet riddled with memory holes".
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] Other commentators have disagreed with Wales, pointing to problems such as Google including links to revenge porn sites in its search results, and have accused Google of orchestrating a publicity campaign to escape the burdensome obligation to comply with the law.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] In response to the criticism, the EU has released a factsheet to address what it considers myths about the right to be forgotten.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] In addition to this, for further clarification of the law, the factsheet provides information about the important court case C-131/12 and frequently asked questions regarding Google, the purpose of the law, and how it works.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] Other criticisms involving the right to be forgotten concerns the policies for data removal regarding minors.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] The U.S. has laws that protect the privacy of minors.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] The California Minor Eraser Law is a law that allows California residents younger than the age of 18 to request to have information removed that they posted on an online server.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] The law "applies to websites, social media sites, mobile apps and other online services" and follows "Europe's recognition of the 'right to be forgotten'".
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] This law became effective on January 1, 2015 and remains in existence.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] Online "service" operators that have services "directed toward minors" must update their privacy policies to include the option to remove data if requested by a minor that is posted on a service.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] In the UK, the 2017 Conservative manifesto included a pledge to allow social media platform users to remove outdated information that was posted when they were younger than the age of 18.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] "A Tory victory on the 8th of June will lead to those youthful indiscretions on Facebook and Twitter being open to erasure.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] But there are also plans to fine social media firms for not moving at the speed of political opportunism over extreme content." The United Kingdom has not yet fully adopted the ruling of the European Court of Justice regarding the right to be forgotten and argued to keep it from becoming EU law.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] However, in the upcoming elections in the UK laws could be passed to allow minors to remove embarrassing posts or photos on social media that could come back to affect job applications or public image in later life.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] Theresa May, then Prime Minister of the UK, has advocated to extend privacy rights for minors in allowing them to have a right to delete information.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] The intentions for this extension of privacy are based on the fact that social media sites store years of data that affect minors lives' much later after the information is posted.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] May gave her stance on privacy when she said, "'The Internet has brought a wealth of opportunity but also significant new risks which have evolved faster than society's response to them'".
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] The Conservative Party, which was headed by May from 2016 to 2019, has pushed for policies that aggressively remove illegal material from the Internet and fine firms that do not take action in removing said material.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] In 2015, Commission nationale de l'informatique et des libertés (CNIL) asked Google to remove data from all versions available in any part of the world.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] Google and other entities argued that European data regulators should not be allowed to decide what Internet users around the world find when they use a search engine.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] Security researchers from CISPA, Saarland University and the University of Auckland are working to develop software to support the automation of the right to be forgotten in a scalable, provable and privacy-preserving manner.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] The team's software, Oblivion, would automate the process of verifying someone's personal information can be found in a Google search result, to help Google staff manage the high volume of take-down requests.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] Researchers have noted that the current capabilities of this technology have some limitations.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] The software can only determine whether a piece of information is available, not whether it should be removed.
[src:ccpa-privacy/right-to-be-forgotten] Data deletion protocols concerning the death of a user is another consideration.
